One of our companions has a gluten intolerance and follows a vegetarian diet, and after inquiring about the menu options, she ordered an omelet skillet, which initially came with asparagus, but was subsequently substituted with mushrooms, spinach, and goat cheese.  She reported that the vegetables were extremely fresh, and she enjoyed the dish.  I opted for the Brisket sliders and a side of house-made potato crisps, which were supposedly coated with extra virgin olive oil and baked, not fried.  However, I found the chips to be excessively greasy and overcooked, whereas my gluten-free, vegetarian companion found them to be addictive.  The brisket sliders were praised by one of the co-owners as the best they have ever tasted, but I found some of the meat to be tough to chew, and the leftovers were fatty and sinewy the next day.  Not a dish I would order again.  Linda decided to order a dessert to share, the baked cinnamon-pecan French toast, which looked so appealing that I eventually gave in and tried it, despite having a pecan allergy.  I managed to enjoy the caramelized toast pieces without the nuts, but I hope the kitchen will consider offering alternative nut-based desserts in the future.

After a couple of hours spent admiring (and listening to) various instruments, I and a friend, Violeta, decided to meet up at a local eatery.

The venue was quite vibrant!  It was 1 pm, and there were two distinct sections within this room.  While they shared the same furniture, one area felt like a quaint coffee shop, with a rounded counter adorned with baked goods and deli cases stocked with bottles of water, juices, and other items, the specifics of which I do not recall, as we opted to sit in the other section, which had a more "open" ambiance to it.  Large glass windows allowed nature to envelop us, at least to a certain extent, and, in my opinion, it felt like a lively, green bistro (and I mention this in a loving and respectful manner).  I wished there were more servers on hand, as it seemed there was only one.  We waited for some time for tables to be cleared.  Eventually, I had to approach him to ask if he would clean up our table.  Had I not been in a rush to sit and unwind while waiting for our food to arrive before departing for school, I wouldn't have minded the wait as much.

I appreciated the organic, upscale feel to the place, and the busyness of the cooks, who looked as though they should be working at a high-end steakhouse, and the presentations of the menus and dishes made us feel as though we were indeed paying for quality.  The menus hinted at the use of local produce and the occasional organic item, but I would like to see higher-quality oils being used namely, a rejection of GM soybean, canola, cottonseed, and corn oils!  I enjoyed my 6 oz. grass-fed burger and perfectly crisped and seasoned sweet potato fries.  Next time, I plan to check out the desserts.  Some looked absolutely decadent!

P.S.  I was not pleased with having to retrieve my own utensils or napkins.  The atmosphere calls for utensils wrapped in cloth, and placed on the table, not sitting in metal holders, like one would find at a buffet or in a workplace cafeteria.  The paper napkins were of high-quality, super-absorbent material, I must say.

On a particular day in May 2012, a strong yearning for a chocolate croissant had been building up for several days, prompting the decision to finally sample the offerings at a local establishment.  Although the time was still early in the afternoon, the available pastries and desserts were limited in number.  The intention was to try an almond and a chocolate croissant, but unfortunately, the former had sold out.  Three chocolate croissants remained (along with a few raisins), so one was ordered to take away.  The decision was made to try it before departing to determine if the rest were needed...  Needless to say, all three were taken home.

The price was $2.70, plus tax, per chocolate croissant.  Unfortunately, there was not enough time to sample the local coffee.  Perhaps next time, when a visit is planned earlier in the day to secure an almond croissant, or two.

The arrangement of the tables for service was pleasing to the eye - the atmosphere already exuded romance.  The anticipation is growing to try dinner here soon...  A selection of three different desserts caught the eye in the display cases, as well as some delectable-looking truffles.

A week ago, during the happy hour, the culinary experience consisted of a dish of squid rings coated in a saffron-enriched batter, accompanied by a glass of a specific red wine produced by a renowned winemaker, and a dessert prepared with brandy. The dinner rolls served were particularly enjoyable. Upon being presented with the squid dish, one of the first things that caught my attention was its vibrant hue. I inquired whether it was saffron that imparted this color, and I was assured that it was indeed saffron-infused batter that was used... The presentation of the squid rings was indeed visually appealing, and they were savored for their taste. The accompanying aioli was straightforward yet pleasing. As for the dessert, a deal was proposed to me that if I did not consider it the best dessert I had ever tasted, the full price of $7 would not be charged. Although it was not the best I had ever had (a family member is renowned for her exceptional dessert-making skills, and even I possess a certain aptitude for creating an impressive dessert), it was still remarkably good, and I did not see the need to be dishonest about it, so I paid the full amount. Willingly. 

The next visit featured a dish of frog legs and a drink made from a mixture of wine and other fruits.

Two communications from a certain individual, identified only by the pseudonym "Iolanda," were received this morning.  Some readers may find the content of these messages entertaining.  It is clear that the writer will not be revisiting a specific location, 98 South.  The information contained within may be of assistance to some readers.  By the way, a particular type of person is often the subject of ridicule.  It is indeed simpler to issue insults when one is able to conceal one's identity.

A short time ago: Envy, rather than a counterargument, seems to be a familiar companion to the writer.

A few minutes ago: Initially, the drink was assumed to be intended for someone else, but it was ultimately left behind by the writer.  It would be unwise for the writer to have their image publicly displayed.  A certain area, known as the "west side," may be the writer's preferred destination.  The writer appears to be in a celebratory mood.

Approximately five or six years ago, a dear sibling presented me with a lovely container of Aveda Soothing Aqua Therapy as a Christmas gift.  I had long been eager to try the product, yet felt unable to justify spending twenty-four dollars on sixteen ounces of bath salts (the price has since increased to thirty dollars).  The container was part of a gift package, but Aveda does not typically offer discounts on its products.  Nevertheless, I appreciate being able to customize gift selections to include specific products that I know the individual I am gifting holds in high esteem.  

If you are ever uncertain about what to give someone for the holidays, a birthday, or any other special occasion, you may wish to try your luck at any Aveda location all the women I know appreciate Aveda products (some claim they do not, but secretly do and simply dislike paying premium prices for them!).  You might say, "But what if the person I am gifting is a male?"  I shall let you in on a secret males also appreciate Aveda pampering, as I have discovered by purchasing hair products, mint soaps, and after shaves from this establishment, and even the most rugged males beam with joy when they find themselves the fortunate recipients!  Hehe.

In any case, back to that jar of soothing salts I was discussing... I have been rationing my use of the salts for special occasions, such as when I exhaust my supply of generic Epsom salts*, or when my collection of Aura Cacia Pure Aromatherapy Foam Bath sampler pack fails to appeal to me at the time.  I am disheartened to think that after tonight's wonderful bath, I shall only have enough for one more blissful soak...  I am aware that I could acquire a brand-new jar for future baths, but some things in life are simply more satisfying when they are gifted, don't you agree?  Hmm... Valentine's Day is drawing near...

I wish I could award this particular establishment five stars, but based on the last few visits (once or twice a year), I am unable to do so, as the prior excellent level of customer service I had received has significantly diminished.  Gone are the enthusiastic, yet warm greetings, and I am rarely, if at all, greeted with a hot cup of licorice-mint tea, anymore.  Nevertheless, I still appreciate the products, even though I almost-always now acquire them at Tempe's Moodswings salon...

*Helpful hint:  Epsom salt baths are beneficial after receiving massages; a soak helps to significantly reduce soreness you may sometimes experience after an intense session by reducing inflammation.  I know, because I used to say "alright" when my former therapist would suggest a soak until I finally did so one day, and wouldn't you know it, it really did help!  I now almost never omit a soak after a session, even if hours may pass before I have the opportunity!

A certain demographic receives a discounted rate on a specific day of the week, which is Thursday.  Otherwise, the standard rate of $9.50 applies to all patrons, except for a particular group that may be eligible for a reduced price, as of 6 p.m.  It is indeed fortunate that parking is complimentary for up to four hours!  In a more uplifting context, one has the opportunity to engage in a brief, yet invigorating physical activity, which can be accomplished in a quarter of an hour or more, prior to attending a film.  There is a certain satisfaction in ascending and descending a staircase of multiple levels.

On November 22, 2010, I experienced a slight hiccup while navigating unfamiliar city roads, which, coupled with the fact that my mind was preoccupied, caused me to miss my intended exit.  However, once I found the parking facility, the rest of the journey was uneventful.  I managed to save some money by choosing this parking option over long-term airport parking.  While booking my flights online, I stumbled upon a parking service called FastTrack.  Before finalizing my parking purchase, I decided to verify the service's website, and to my surprise, it was cheaper than the rate provided by Orbitz.  It's worth noting that customers can choose between covered and uncovered parking, with the former being more expensive, of course.  During our interaction with the shuttle service, we encountered two different drivers.  While the first driver was courteous, the second one went above and beyond by exiting the shuttle to assist with our luggage, not just once, but twice, when we boarded and disembarked at the parking lot.  He even took the trouble of placing our roll-ons directly into my vehicle.  I was so impressed that I showed my appreciation with a more substantial tip.  The shuttle service operates on a regular schedule, picking up passengers at the airport and transporting them to the parking lot.  However, passengers can contact the dispatcher at any time using the phone number provided by the driver to ensure a driver is on the way.  We were thoroughly satisfied with the service and look forward to using it again in the future.

. It was on November 30, 2010, that I had a somewhat underwhelming experience at a certain establishment.  The overall rating I would give is 2.5 stars.

I stopped by during happy hour, but unfortunately, the happy hour food menu did not have anything that caught my eye.  Therefore, I decided to order a medium Emilia Romagna pizza, which featured mozzarella, parmesan, and a 12-year-old balsamic vinegar called Aceto Balsamico.  I do not recall the exact price of this pizza, but it was likely in the vicinity of $14.  However, the pizza arrived at my table with a slightly overcooked bottom crust, and the very thin crust failed to retain its crispiness for an extended period, lasting only about 5 minutes, and it became soggy by the 10-minute mark.  Although I enjoyed the slice I had at the restaurant, the leftovers proved to be excessively salty when I attempted to reheat the pizza at home, which made me regret the purchase, in my opinion.  I only consumed one slice at the establishment because I wanted to try the cobbler of the day, which was an apple cobbler topped with Haagen-Daaz ice cream, if I am not mistaken.  I had to order it without powdered sugar due to a corn allergy, and I found it satisfactory, and not overly sweet.  I would be interested in trying their other cobblers as well, but the high price tag of $9, combined with the fact that the ice cream contains corn syrup, which I am allergic to, is a significant deterrent.  I would also like to try their profiteroles, but they come with a price of $9 as well, which works out to $4.50 per profiterole, and I was quoted that two profiteroles come in a serving.  One should not be misled by the stern expression of the bartender, who, despite his gruff demeanor, was friendly to talk to on our initial interaction.  However, a couple of friends and I visited the establishment after a mixer about a month ago, and the bartender seemed unapproachable and projected an air of being too busy to engage with us beyond taking our order.  There was no greeting or inquiry about our well-being that evening, which was a major turn-off, and considering the high prices on their menu, I do not think I will be returning. 

(Prior to writing this review, I had intended to rate the establishment 3 stars, but after completing it, I have decided to rate it 2 stars.  I wish you a more pleasant experience at this establishment.)

8/06.
Initial Visit.  Happy Hour.  Ordered two morsels: a Philadelphia roll and a spicy salmon roll, deep-fried and topped with roe.  It is common for most sushi establishments to accommodate substitution requests, especially when they involve avoiding allergens, and doing so without extra charge.  Not so at this particular eatery.  I have been assured by individuals in similar positions that they would be more than happy to make such substitutions without taking offense, yet this chef seemed to be an exception.  Therefore, the photos of the dishes served will reflect any recipe modifications.  I ordered a glass of house pinot grigio, which unfortunately contained an unwanted impurity; however, this issue was quickly resolved.  

Regrettably, there were limited Happy Hour options available.  The servers were courteous, but the sushi chef displayed a visibly disgruntled expression when I had to return a dish due to it containing an allergen that I had specifically requested to be avoided.  While I could understand a slight miscommunication, I was surprised by the chef's reaction given that the list of allergens was clearly noted on a piece of paper right in front of him.  This was not a trivial mistake, as it occurred on the second of two dishes.  

The ambiance of the establishment is nothing to write home about.  I did, however, appreciate the distinctive red mosaic tile in the women's restroom, which provided a pleasant contrast to the predominantly black dcor.

I recently had the pleasure of sampling a certain Bavarian cream donut that left me utterly speechless... and somewhat repentant!  Its silky texture and sultry appearance were nothing short of captivating, elevating this classic variety to new heights.  Be warned, though: partaking in this indulgence may result in a rather...morning-after regret.  Proceed with caution, dear friends.

It was a lovely serenade that greeted us at the entrance of the restaurant, a picturesque waterfall that beckoned us in!  The evening was quite cool, and I had a hunch that our elderly relative, who shall remain unnamed, might not be thrilled about dining al fresco, but I requested a table on the patio nonetheless.  Upon noticing the strategically placed heaters, I felt reassured that we'd be comfortable.  What a delightful surprise it was to be seated next to the soothing waterfall that we had encountered upon entering!  The anxiety that had been building up over our elderly relative's potential discomfort was for naught; in fact, she even expressed feeling a bit too warm!  Fortunately, her cousin quickly swapped places with her grandmother.

We shared some mouth-watering saganaki, an award-winning gyro dinner consisting of lamb and beef, delectable rice, sauted vegetables, and perfectly roasted potatoes, accompanied by a side Greek salad, and a decadent galaktoboureka for dessert - a custard baked in flaky phyllo, topped with vanilla ice cream, flamed, and drizzled with caramel sauce.  We three ended up overindulging, but no one complained.  Our elderly relative had never experienced Greek cuisine before, so this enchanting evening, complete with outdoor dining, the ambiance of lit palm trees, the waterfall, and the delicious food, served as a perfect farewell for her, who had been feeling homesick on US soil for six long months.  She departed for her homeland the previous day, on a Monday.  I hope she's happier back home... Our elderly relative, next time you're savoring a refreshing mango shake, I hope you'll think of me!  I'll be there in spirit, sipping on another drink beside you.

Firstly, a major drawback: the lighting was woefully inadequate.  Firstly, my eyes were unable to fully appreciate the beauty that lay before me.  Secondly, the photos taken would likely be ruined.  Thankfully, my cousin's digital camera had a better flash.  Please refer to the accompanying photos.

Secondly, the service was underwhelming.  Our appetizer was served, yet we didn't have any utensils on our table.  We were unable to locate our server, so I had to fetch three sets from a nearby table.  Moreover, we almost missed the impressive flame shows of both saganaki and galaktoboureka.  My cousin and our elderly relative thought something or someone had caught fire (in the event of a person, not so amusing); the presenter should have given us a warning before setting the cheese ablaze.  

Thirdly, the restroom was in a deplorable state of disarray.  The counter was wet all over, and the floor was littered with paper.  This was a stark contrast to the wonderful ambiance we experienced on the patio (excluding the poor lighting, of course).

On a certain day in November, I found myself in a particular location awaiting the commencement of a certain event, which was due to begin in thirty minutes. However, my stomach was growling, and I had already consumed a second meal for the day consisting of sweet baked goods and wine, which I had not deemed a healthy choice to conclude the evening. Consequently, I decided to investigate a nearby eatery called Red Devil. Upon entering, I discovered that it was deserted, with only a couple present for dinner, and I sensed that the majority of the evening's business would likely be take-out orders.

The bartender was initially amenable, but his demeanor changed when I inquired about the ingredients. Although he remained courteous, his smiles vanished. I was on the verge of rising from my seat and departing. When the food arrived twenty-five minutes later, I regretted not having left earlier.

The calzone crust was soggy, devoid of any crispiness, and the mozzarella-ricotta mixture formed an unappetizing, flavorless conglomeration. I failed to detect any ricotta flavor. The marinara sauce, however, was the sole redeeming aspect of the dish. Nonetheless, what good is a sauce if the food it accompanies is not worth consuming? I had the leftovers boxed and stood up to depart after only spending five minutes eating. I had a social engagement to attend, after all.

P.S. I am an abysmal example of an environmental advocate, for no sooner had I exited the doors of Red Devil's than I seized the first opportunity to discard the leftovers in the trash. I should have left them on the table in the first place.

As I sat in the waiting area of a certain automotive repair establishment (where we had a spare hour to kill), I pondered the idea of treating my mother and myself to a hearty breakfast at a popular eatery nearby (I had previously only visited it for lunch).  However, upon observing the lengthy queue of individuals waiting to gain entry, I decided we would opt for lunch at a different establishment, AE, which had received glowing endorsements from the manager of a nearby business (conveniently located directly across the street from the aforementioned shop).  

The dining area was Spartan in design, featuring cafeteria-style tables and chairs, as well as TVs and window counter seating.  A self-service counter offered complimentary coffee and tea, accompanied by Splenda for those who preferred to sweeten their beverages.  The breakfast menu appeared quite enticing, but the individual behind the counter informed me that the delivery person responsible for the eggs would not arrive for another 10 minutes or so (perhaps a feta omelette would have been a suitable choice?).  I decided to try the Friday special of grilled tilapia served atop a salad and accompanied by a gyro pita with a side salad, extra feta.  Unfortunately, the tilapia proved to be a frustrating meal, as it would inexplicably break into tiny pieces the moment I attempted to cut it with a fork or knife.  Furthermore, the dish was rather unpalatable due to my decision to forego the house-made vinaigrette (which contained allergens); fortunately, the extra feta (I am a great admirer of feta!) helped to salvage the dish, and I was able to consume the fish without the use of a spoon, which I had been wishing for throughout the meal.  The gyro pita, on the other hand, was a more enjoyable experience, although my mother did not appreciate the meat.  To be honest, it did not compare favourably to the gyro dinner I had enjoyed a few nights prior at a different establishment, but for the price (approximately $6), it made for a quick and satisfying lunch (and the extra feta in the pita was an added bonus)!  Although the gyro is not prepared in-house, the eatery does have it shipped in three times a week from a city located in the Midwest, according to the individual behind the counter.  

The baklava looked exceptionally appealing, but I was unable to try it due to the presence of an allergen; however, I was confident that any item on the menu would have been sufficient to satisfy my hunger!

Two Tuesdays ago, I partook in a culinary experience at a particular eatery, where they offered double-stamp rewards on that specific day.  The pancake I ordered, made from whole wheat, was generously sized, measuring the same diameter as the plate it was served on, which is their standard practice.  Unfortunately, my experience at their Central Avenue location this past Monday did not live up to my expectations.  For lunch, I had ordered an omelette called the Isle of Capri, which was a decent portion, served with an English muffin and country potatoes, and was more than sufficient for two people.  I had intended to take a photo, but the presentation did not lend itself well to being captured in a styrofoam box.  Do not let the aroma of feta and olives deter you from trying the omelette, as it is truly delectable.

It was a truly enchanting atmosphere inside.  The vista overlooking the brick oven was particularly captivating.  The salad and sandwich I enjoyed during my midday meal with a companion were truly exceptional.  Unfortunately, I was not equally impressed with the pizza I had for supper... However, I must confess a preference for thin-crust pizzas, and the pie I had was far too thick and doughy to my taste.  I took a pie home for my mother, and she was not enamored with it either.  

I did appreciate the outdoor seating area, although I had arrived too early for the soft glow of the candles to create a fully romantic ambiance for me.  The neighborhood ambiance did spark a wistful longing in me to reside downtown...

I've made a few visits to this establishment a couple of years ago, during my time residing in Chandler.  This is a venue that numerous individuals of Vietnamese descent frequently recommend to me when I inquire about Pho (colleagues and nail technicians alike).  However, this was prior to the proliferation of newer pho establishments.  

I've never been particularly enthusiastic about pho, and I'm uncertain if I've even tried it here.  I have sampled a few appetizers and stir-fries, and I must confess that none have been noteworthy enough to warrant a mention (or, more fittingly, none are deserving of online endorsement).  The outdated/old-fashioned dcor is also unimpressive.  I would say that the sole redeeming quality of Saigon Pho, at least from my perspective, is the server Crystal.  She is very friendly, efficient, and always prepared with suggestions based on what the customer prefers.

07/16/11

A visit to a local eatery took place on this day.  I arrived ahead of a companion and was seated at a table for two.  A dinner menu was handed to me, but I had to request the Yelp Eats menu, which was a peculiarity since the other restaurants visited during the promotion had provided it as part of the initial menu presentation.  Upon receiving the YE menu, I noticed a sticker that cautioned against sharing dishes, which was another unusual aspect of this dining experience.  While waiting for my friend to arrive, I ordered a mojito ($7.50) and inquired about certain dishes to our server, who displayed impressive knowledge of both food and beverage options.  The mojito, crafted with dark rum, fresh lime, muddled mint, sugar, and a splash of soda, arrived as my friend arrived, and she also ordered one for herself.  It is highly recommended to try their mojito, which I found to be one of the best I have ever had, aside from those I have made myself.  The drink was not overly sweet, and the rum was not overpowering, yet it still had a potent effect.

Following a brief conversation, we placed our orders, opting for the Bistec Encevollado (steak with onions) and the Frituras de Frijoles Negros (black bean fritters with avocado dip).  Despite my initial statement that I would be skipping appetizers to leave room for dessert, our server asked me at least twice if I wanted to order an appetizer, pointing to the appetizer section of the menu on the second inquiry.  I reiterated my decision to order an entree, while my friend planned to start with an appetizer and then order an entree.  Our server's persistence made us feel pressured and somewhat unwelcome.  My friend eventually ordered another appetizer and a dessert.  The appetizer and steak arrived together, and I offered my friend a taste of the steak, but she declined due to her preference for not consuming too much red meat.  She did, however, enjoy the Papas de la Casa (spicy homestyle potatoes), which she described as highly seasoned, although I had not noticed they were spicy.  My friend tried to share her fritters with me, but I had already tried them before and preferred to focus on my steak.  Fortunately, our server had encouraged my friend to order a second dish, which turned out to be the Frituras de Camarones (three crispy shrimp pancakes served with a Romesco sauce), which she enjoyed.  I was correct in my observation that the sauce contained nuts, and my friend described its flavor as pepperiness and acidity, with notes of almonds and sherry.  I thoroughly enjoyed the Bistec encevollado and would not hesitate to order it again.

Our server inquired several times if we were ready to order dessert, but I decided to wait for my friend to finish eating.  I was still savoring my mojito and contemplating ordering another.  Eventually, I decided to order the chocolate bread pudding with homemade dark fudge rum sauce, while my friend opted for the lime pie.  Both desserts were enjoyable, but I preferred the pie.  The fudge rum sauce, however, was exceptional, and I found myself wanting more.  I restrained myself from taking more of my friend's pie, knowing I would have another opportunity to enjoy it at home.  We plan to return to this location, especially on Mojito Mondays, and hope that the rudeness we experienced was an isolated incident due to Yelp Eats Week.  It would be a shame to skip this location, as my friend mentioned that it is less noisy than the one on Camelback.  I should have probably not tipped 20% of the original cost, considering the server's behavior, but I wanted to avoid giving the impression that Yelpers are cheap.

p.s.  Upon entering the restaurant, I was struck by a strong odor, which I later realized was due to onions.  If I had not been meeting a friend, I might have left and gone elsewhere.

p.p.s.  The Cuban bread was truly exceptional!

On 7/1/10, I had been meaning to try Tortas El Guero for a couple of weeks, and a friend's enthusiastic recommendation finally prompted me to pay a visit during my next days off.  I arrived before 4:30 p.m., only to find that the individual behind the counter was unable to communicate in English at all.  Fortunately, I still retained a basic grasp of Spanish, which allowed me to request that a few ingredients be left out.  If I had waited until 5 p.m., I would have had no trouble with the bilingual server who arrived later.  

I opted for the carne asada torta, and the bread was satisfactory.  However, the filling was somewhat lacking.  In my opinion, Tortas El Guero should either use smaller-sized bread or increase the filling to make the sandwich more filling.  The price of the sandwich was undoubtedly too high, and I wouldn't order it again at that price, especially when I could get an equally satisfying, if not superior, serving at Phoenix Ranch Market, whose telera bread is truly exceptional.  As a result, I had to order two side tacos, which contained the meat I wanted (pastor and carne asada), to supplement the torta.  Based on what I tasted, I would consider ordering the pastor if I were to return, but I do not think that I will be going back.

On the seventh of February, two thousand and ten, a certain individual opted for take-out from a popular eatery known as Whitey's, which served a white cheese pizza accompanied by alfredo sauce and garlic.  Unfortunately, the crust was overly thick, resulting in a complete lack of crispy texture.  The flavour was merely satisfactory, not quite sufficient to prompt a repeat order from this particular customer; they also experienced some adverse reactions due to an allergy, which is a common occurrence at large chain establishments like the one in question.  The customer attempted to reheat a couple of slices the following day, but they failed to regain their former crispiness and the flavours had faded, forcing the customer to discard the remaining slices.  It is regrettable that this eatery did not meet expectations, as it would have been a convenient option for take-out when visiting friends in the surrounding area.

After a recent episode of a popular travel show, my taste buds began craving the South Indian delicacy known as dosa.  After much deliberation between two local eateries, Udupi Cafe and Taj Mahal, I decided to revisit Udupi Cafe, a place I had previously tried but not thoroughly explored.  

Upon perusing the dosa menu, I opted for the Udupi Special spring dosa, a variation I had not yet encountered.  I inquired about the presence of certain allergens in the dosa and its accompanying chutneys, and was assured by my server that the dosa itself was safe, while two out of three chutneys (coconut and jalapeno-cilantro) were off-limits, but the sambar was acceptable.  The server even pointed out an allergen in the coconut chutney, which surprised me, as I had previously been informed that the sambar contained allergens at other restaurants.  My server offered to substitute the other two chutneys with tamarind sauce, and I decided to trust his knowledge, taking a bite of the sambar and discovering a flavorful chunk of potato and broth.  It was a delightful experience!  However, upon further inspection, I spotted something that made me hesitant.  Just as I was about to take another bite, my server and the host approached me, warning me not to eat the sambar or dosa as they contained allergens.  I was shocked and disappointed!  So, I had to abandon my Udupi special spring dosa and sambar, and was left uncertain about what to order.  I knew I had a few hours of discomfort ahead of me, which unfortunately began to manifest as I was signing my credit card receipt.

At this point, the host advised me to avoid the dosa menu, as the kitchen staff could not prepare a filling without a certain ingredient that was problematic for me.  Normally, this wouldn't be a major issue, as there are many other dosa options that can be paired with chutneys.  However, since the three chutneys also contained an ingredient I couldn't have, and the chef couldn't prepare the sauces without it, I had to rule out dosa from Udupi Cafe.  I decided to opt for the assorted appetizer platter instead, which would have been accompanied by tamarind sauce if not for my request for a second option, plain yogurt.  The host suggested adding carrots to the yogurt to give it flavor, and I agreed.  The three items I enjoyed from the platter were cauliflower pakora, the samosa, and the veggie cutlet.  While I appreciated the samosa and cauliflower pakora, I was less fond of the dense mysore bonda and the bready medhu vada, although they were enjoyable when dipped in tamarind sauce and yogurt.  In retrospect, I wished the meal had not been dominated by fried items.  

Given Udupi Cafe's reluctance to modify their dishes to accommodate certain dietary needs, which led me to believe that many items are pre-made and later plated, and the staff's hesitation to create a simple chutney, I doubt I will continue to prioritize Udupi Cafe for my future Indian cuisine cravings.  There are many other options to explore.  I wish Udupi Cafe and its management and staff the best in catering to vegetarians and omnivores alike, offering a menu that is 100% vegetarian.  I highly recommend trying the Gobi Manchurian, which was delicious! 

I did manage to capture some captivating photographs during my meal, which was a silver lining.  I wish I had a close-up shot of the veggie cutlet and the samosa...

On a specific date in June, I accompanied a family member to a dining establishment for my second visit, marking their first.  We ordered a small salad with a unique name and a large pizza with a specific topping combination.  The salad arrived relatively quickly, despite our server having placed the order before inquiring about our pizza preferences.  (Our pizza, however, took a bit longer to arrive, as the kitchen staff had to take extra time to thoroughly clean the oven's surface to minimize the risk of an allergic reaction.)  I assure you, the wait was well worth it.

The salad comprised a medley of greens, sliced tomatoes, crunchy walnuts, crumbled feta cheese, and a high-quality balsamic vinaigrette that can be purchased for take-home use.  This salad was truly delectable and enjoyable to consume (the combination of textures and flavors was the key to its simplicity and charm!), and I could envision myself ordering a small portion as a main course and being completely satisfied.  In fact, I was thoroughly content with my half of the salad and could have left to attend a scheduled movie, but we had to wait approximately thirty minutes for the pizza to be ready.  No cause for concern, however, as the pizza was even more exceptional than the one I had previously tried.  (If you've read my previous review, you'll recall how much I appreciated the specific combination of toppings.)  Unfortunately, the images of the pizza I've included here are subpar... (My laptop is currently in for repairs, and I'm unable to adjust the lighting.)

There are several dates that stand out in my mind.  One of them is 12/20/12.

2.5 out of five stars.

Upon hearing about the DBG's dazzling displays during Las Noches de las Luminarias, I had envisioned something truly spectacular.  While I have been impressed by the creativity of bedazzled homes, malls, and restaurants in recent years, the DBG's plastic replicas of brown paper bags with votives and lights strung around trees now seem somewhat unimpressive.  I must admit, however, that I was occasionally mesmerized by the beauty of it all, particularly when I caught sight of a towering Christmas tree aglow with lights, and around a few bends, where pillars of lights wrapped around the rooftops of a couple of buildings beckoned me to draw closer, accompanied by the smooth strains of jazz music that seemed to caress my ears like soft silken ribbons...  Perhaps it was just a particularly crowded evening - I didn't realize it at the time, but there was a special promotion for the Luminarias exhibit: buy one, get one free, with a reduced admission price of $12.50 per person, down from $25.  The sheer number of attendees made it difficult to navigate the area, and at one point, my companion and I were forced to backtrack, as there was no clear path around the dense crowd.  I felt sorry for the families with members in wheelchairs, as it was freezing, dark, and hazardous to navigate the crowded pathways.

In an ideal situation, with a partner to share the experience with and fewer people around, I might have enjoyed myself more.  Nonetheless, I don't think it's worth the $25 per person admission fee on any ordinary day!  (I'd much rather take a brisk walk around my own block a few times for some exercise and spend $50 on some mood lighting for my home, I'm confident I would appreciate it for a longer period than a single evening at the DBG!)

I am at a loss as to what has become of my reviews for a particular U.S. establishment that serves egg dishes... yet I must confess that I have a genuine affection for their protein pancakes. This eatery is a compact venue, so patrons are well-advised to allocate a generous amount of time on weekendsvisitors would do well to arrive before 10 a.m. or, alternatively, wait until after 11:30 a.m. Breakfast service concludes at precisely 2 p.m. A certain family member of mine holds a special fondness for their skillets; however, I would recommend bypassing their biscuits and gravy altogether.

After a prolonged period of inactivity, I had been putting off having my malfunctioning garbage disposal evaluated for potential repair or replacement, not wanting to incur the expense of a professional visit solely for a minor issue.  However, I found myself in need of a plumber to address a persistent leak from my toilet tank, which had not been resolved by simply shutting off the valve.  I consulted online reviews and discovered a reliable service provider who had received glowing endorsements from satisfied customers.  Given that this service provider had been recommended by a trusted individual, I felt confident in my decision to engage their services.

I contacted the service provider on a Monday, hoping to schedule a visit for the same day or, at the very least, the following Thursday.  However, the service provider informed me that they were fully booked for the day, but offered to visit the next day, which would require me to take a day off from work.  While I was hesitant to take a day off, I was aware that neglecting the issue could lead to more costly and extensive repairs down the line, and that wasting water in a water-scarce region was not an option.

The service provider arrived promptly the following afternoon and completed all the necessary repairs within a 90-minute timeframe.  Furthermore, they also assisted in selecting a replacement garbage disposal from a nearby hardware store, despite initially assuming that the issue was merely a minor problem.  I had also requested that they inspect a second toilet tank that had been causing concerns for a housemate.  Rather than exploiting the situation to inflate the bill, the service provider demonstrated their integrity by informing me that the tank did not require any repairs.  They were more than willing to educate me on how to perform future repairs and even offered to guide me through the process via phone if I chose to tackle the tasks myself.  In line with the sentiments expressed by their previous customers, I found their fees to be reasonable and their demeanor to be amicable and approachable.

Here is the paraphrased text with an increased number of period marks:

4.5 stars were awarded to this establishment, and for good reason.  I've had the pleasure of dining at a certain eatery on multiple occasions, but my latest visit was particularly noteworthy.  A delectable breakfast was in store for me this morning, and it was a meal to remember.  The star of the show was a stack of three fluffy pancakes, priced at $6.5.  A delightful addition to this dish was a generous helping of house-made granola, costing a mere $1.  This was served alongside a savory side of grilled meatballs, priced at $3.5, and a rich double-shot of espresso, which cost $2.  The service was impeccable, with my server being attentive and knowledgeable about the menu.  Unfortunately, I was unable to partake in the market-made maple syrup blend, nor the house-whipped cream, blueberry compote, raspberry and apricot jams, or the flavored syrups available at the coffee counter.  However, I was offered a unique chocolate syrup, crafted from scratch using chocolate, sugar, and coconut oil - a truly exceptional condiment.  It would pair perfectly with ice cream sundaes, I'm sure.  In any case, I didn't require any additional embellishments to enhance my meal, as the pancakes and meatballs complemented each other beautifully.

It's worth noting that this eatery offers a remarkable promotion:  purchase an espresso or specialty coffee, and you'll receive unlimited cups of regular coffee during your meal.  Although I didn't need an extra caffeine boost after my double-shot, I did partake in some of the house-blend coffee.  Following my meal, consisting of 1.5 pancakes, meatballs, and a caffeine boost, I felt invigorated and ready to tackle the day, despite having only four hours of sleep.  Or so I hoped.

P.S.  Despite tipping generously at the counter, I felt that my server, a gentleman by the name of Bruce, deserved even more recognition for his exceptional service.  His patience and courtesy were truly commendable, and it's just one more reason why I hold this establishment in high esteem.

Addendum:  After receiving directions from Bruce on the quickest route to 101 N, he offered me a complimentary cup of coffee to take with me.  I must confess that I have a profound affection for this eatery.  A helpful hint for patrons:  complimentary Wi-Fi can be accessed by entering the code printed at the bottom of your receipt.

I made my maiden voyage to a certain shopping establishment last Thursday, and I must say, I was thoroughly impressed!  I had previously visited this location, albeit briefly, to return some items at a now-defunct footwear store.  This time, however, my mission was to procure a few items of olive-hued body butter and shower gel for a family member.  A significant advantage of this particular mall is that it is situated adjacent to a renowned confectionery store, See's Candies, which is conveniently located on the north side of Tatum Boulevard.

Upon a cursory inspection, I observed that the mall features an Express store, as well as several other retailers that I had not encountered before.  I would have liked to explore these shops further, but my primary objective at the moment is to acquire organic attire for work and leisure purposes, and I am not aware of any other malls in the region that cater to this specific need.  The mall also boasts a children's play area and a standalone Costco store.  Unfortunately, I was unable to access the wholesale club from the mall's exit, as the entrance was not conveniently located, and I was short on time.  Perhaps next time!

In any case, this particular mall has exceeded my expectations.  It is a far more suitable destination for me than Arizona Mills or Tempe Marketplace.  Given that a prominent mall in Scottsdale has ceased to operate, I will be visiting this shopping complex more frequently in the future, particularly when I require a monthly chocolate fix.  I must admit, however, that I was not aware of the true nature of Spencer's, a store that I discovered to be a purveyor of adult novelties.  I stumbled upon some intriguing items in their novelty section, and I was also made aware of a few individuals who seemed to be familiar with the store.  I was amused by the manner in which a sales associate bid farewell to a couple of young teenagers as they exited the store, which led me to believe that they were regular customers.

**Date:** 12/2/20**20**

2.5 stars.**

I accompanied a young family member to happy hour and took a seat at the bar; this was her first visit to this establishment.  Although I genuinely appreciate the aesthetic and the ambiance of the bar's island layout, I often feel out of place when I sit there.  (In fact, I have attempted to sit at the bar on multiple occasions when dining alone, but ultimately moved to a table.  If it hadn't been for my companion, I probably would have relocated to a table again, or, worse still, departed the restaurant, a decision I've made previously.)  Despite several attempts to persuade her to try a cocktail, she declined, and I therefore opted to order a glass of wine.  I remain perplexed as to why it's so difficult to sample a few wines before making a selection here.  (Just a few nights prior, while dining at a different establishment, my server offered to provide me with samples of the wines I was having trouble choosing!)

We decided to try the Italian Sausage flatbread and the hummus appetizer.  The flatbread, featuring delectable and spicy Italian sausage chunks, consisted of a crispy crust topped with vibrant red piquillo peppers and creamy goat cheeseI would order this again, even though I'm not particularly fond of peppers.  The hummus was equally delightful, accompanied by house-made pita bread and a "petite Greek salad," which comprised only sliced red grape tomatoes and chopped cucumbers (a combination that I'm not fond of!) and an abundance of feta on top.  I'm unsure why the salad was placed directly on top of the hummus, rather than on the side, and not a single leaf of lettuce in sight.  I suppose, given the price of the appetizer, I shouldn't expect an abundance of vegetables, but it would have been pleasant to be able to select the cucumbers.  As served, with the salad placed atop the hummus, which appeared to have been baked for a few minutes before receiving the salad treatment, removing the cucumbers would have resulted in a significant loss of the delicious baked hummus goodness.  And we wouldn't have wanted any of that!

I truly wished we could have stayed past 6 p.m. to observe the celebrity guest bartender, but we had other appointments to attend to.  My companion thoroughly enjoyed the food and the atmosphere here, and I would have awarded this review an additional 4 stars if it weren't for the fact that our bartender displayed a rather unfriendly demeanor when I inquired about sampling the two wines before ordering.  

For your information, the happy hour menu has undergone significant changes, with the selection drastically reduced to approximately 8 items or fewer, down from nearly all of the appetizers and half of the flatbreads and a couple of salads that the previous happy hour menu offered.  Recalling this, along with the wine and salad/hummus incidents, I may be forced to bid farewell to this establishment for an extended period of time...

It's been a while since I was a member of a renowned botanical institution in a Midwestern city.  When I relocated to the Southwestern region in 2003 and became familiar with the Desert Botanical Garden, I immediately purchased a year-long membership without first exploring it in person.  Given the arid climate of my new surroundings, it was only to be expected that the DBG would showcase an impressive variety of succulents.  Perhaps I visited during the wrong seasons, but I left feeling somewhat underwhelmed.  I must confess that I was unfair in comparing these gardens to those in my former city, which boasted an impressive 26 gardens across 385 acres.  Each garden deserves to be appreciated on its own merits.  I did attend a laid-back jazz event that took place on a crisp autumn evening, and the festive tree lights were quite captivating.  Unfortunately, I haven't had the opportunity to attend events like Agave on the Rocks or the Luminaria, nor experience the Chihuly exhibit.  

After reviewing the garden's events calendar, I discovered numerous events that seem quite intriguing.  I may have to consider investing in another membership this year... 

A little-known fact:  Did you know that pineapples and aloe vera are closely related to succulents?

Yesterday, I had the pleasure of dining at a certain breakfast establishment.  On the previous day, I had prepared my own version of honey-buttermilk pancakes, featuring Ghirardelli chocolate chips, sliced bananas, and a sprinkle of cinnamon-roasted almonds, which I had acquired at a well-known wholesale club.  Although my homemade creation was a satisfying meal, it did not meet the high standards of the protein pancakes I had been craving for two weeks.  Following a routine check-up with my physician and a blood donation, I decided to visit this breakfast eatery to take advantage of a complimentary entree, which I had been holding onto for over a year.

My server, whose name I unfortunately did not record, provided excellent service and recommended that I add dollar pancakes to my order, as I was undecided between pancakes and items from the lunch menu.  After watching two episodes of a popular food television show during my morning exercise routine, I had developed a strong desire for corned beef hash or hash browns.  I ultimately decided on a full stack of pancakes ($7.50) and a side of corned beef hash ($3.95).  As I perused the menu, I noticed that for an additional dollar, I could opt for "today's sweet deal."  My server explained that the choice was between an apple streusel bread pudding with caramel sauce or a strawberry shortcake with house-made strawberry fruit topping.  After ascertaining that the caramel sauce contained corn syrup, I made my selection.

In a surprising turn of events, I ordered a stack of pancakes with sliced bananas, candied slivered almonds, and Ghirardelli chocolate chips, instead of the whole wheat pancakes with blueberry and almond I had been craving.  Fortunately, the pancakes were delicious, with the toasted slivered almonds adding a unique texture that was distinct from the candied almonds I have at home.  The Ghirardelli chocolate chips also cooked more evenly than those I had used in my own recipe.  However, I digress...  The corned beef hash, cooked to a crispy perfection, was savory and satisfying.  While it could have been crisper, it was still enjoyable.  The combination of sweet and salty flavors in the dish was a true delight.  The freshly brewed coffee was strong and well-suited to my tastes, and the thermos on the table allowed me to pour myself another cup at my leisure.  Finally, the strawberry shortcake was the perfect way to conclude my dining experience.  The complimentary coffee to-go was also a lovely touch.

If you are a fan of this breakfast establishment, you may want to take advantage of their gift card promotion, which will expire on December 24th.  By purchasing a gift card worth $25 or more, you will receive $5 off your next meal.

I paid a visit to a certain retail establishment for the first time on Thursday, but unfortunately, I left empty-handed.  A few queries regarding potential food allergies prompted a response that fell short of my expectations.  The sales associate behind the counter seemed entirely uncooperative, and I had to insist on having her contact someone to provide the necessary information.  Considering the cookies in question cost $2.50 each, it is quite astonishing that the associate refused to make a simple call, even when I expressed a genuine interest in purchasing at least two of them.  This, coupled with the fact that I have encountered larger cookies made with natural ingredients at a lower price point elsewhere, left a rather sour taste.  Interestingly, a similar scenario played out at a neighboring store, Chill Out.  The sales associate at that store also declined to contact their cookie supplier, which only reinforced my initial impression.  In light of this experience, I made the decision to refrain from visiting this particular establishment again.

On a particular date, which I shall not specify, I had the pleasure of dining at a local eatery with a close associate.  This was my first return visit since attending a promotional event held at a nearby resort several months prior.  We opted to dine outdoors, as the weather was pleasant, and the restaurant had only just begun to serve dinner, so the indoor area was still empty.  We were famished, so by the time our server arrived to take our drink orders, which consisted of water only, as we had previously imbibed wine at the bar and reception areas, we had also placed our entree requests.  The wild salmon sounded particularly appealing, so we both decided to order it, with my companion choosing fingerling potatoes and I opting for asparagus instead.  When it became apparent that we would not be receiving complimentary bread unless we requested it, and we had to wait at least ten minutes, we inquired about the availability of complimentary bread.  To our delight, it was available, accompanied by delicious marinated olives.

The dishes we ordered were truly sublime!  As you can see from the accompanying photographs, my salmon was incredibly juicy.  The textures were exquisite, commencing with the perfectly-crisped skin, nicely seasoned; then immediately underneath it, the seared, buttered flesh; through the flaky layers, until you reach the tender medium-rare center...  I must confess that even now, as I recall those moments, I am experiencing a shiver run down my spine!  And the accompanying vegetables were equally impressive!  Crunchy, yet delicate asparagus spears flanked by olives, grape tomatoes, artichoke hearts, and fennel!  I must confess that I am craving another meal here!  It's probably time to check out a certain online review website for a gift certificate for another meal here soon...

I was surprised to discover that the restaurant's chef de cuisine is a certain individual by the name of James Siao.  He was kind enough to offer my companion and me a complimentary dessert to share.  All the desserts on the menu that evening sounded appealing, but it was no contest we had to try the tiramisu!  This establishment serves a truly exceptional version a marvel to behold, and so many layers to tantalize the taste buds...  It was so cool and creamy, and the cocoa used was of the highest quality.  This dessert was packed with so much flavor, yet it was very light-tasting (and very light in the stomach, too!).  This tiramisu truly lived up to its name a perfect pick-me-up!

I eagerly look forward to my next visit!

. . . 

5/29/10 . .

4 stars. . .

A certain individual took their parent to a dining establishment on this day. . . It was their parent's inaugural visit, and since the individual had never sampled the calamari appetizer at this eatery, they decided to order it. . . The calamari, which was served atop a generous mound of mizuna, a delightful coating of yuzu dressing, and then topped with a toasted blend of black and white sesame seeds, was truly sublime. . . Had they not ordered the scallops, they would have been content with the calamari appetizer and another round (or two) of the cracked honey-wheat bread and herbed butter. . . However, the day scallops did not disappoint. . . The parent was initially displeased with the individual's choice due to the perceived exorbitant price. . . Nevertheless, upon beholding their dishes, which their server took the liberty of dividing for them (no split plate charge, fortunately!), the parent was amazed. . . They had never seen scallops of such enormity before! . . (The largest they had previously encountered were approximately one inch in diameter.) . . A serving of these came with only three pieces, yet each piece measured about three inches in diameter. . . The cross-sections may have appeared slightly raw, but these were perfectly seared, rest assured. . . Furthermore, while the individual will not attempt it again (due to a severe allergy reaction), the forbidden rice, which sat in a delightfully fragrant cream sauce, was delectable. . . If one is not allergic, they must try it as a side, possibly in conjunction with the scallops. . . (It appears that the entree may have been removed from the menu; a pity, indeed.)

. . 6/2/10 . .

2 stars. . .

This individual had long desired to take their parent to Bloom for happy hour, and after their previous experience with the calamari appetizer, it did not take much persuasion for their parent to accompany them on this day. . .

This individual prefers dining at Bloom during happy hour, as it is often less crowded. . . Consequently, one would expect to receive quicker service. . . Unfortunately, this was not the case today, as the establishment was almost empty. . . Their server took at least ten minutes to take their order for glasses of water. . . It was another ten minutes before they were able to peruse the drink menu. . . Fortunately, the happy hour food menu is worth revisiting, and they will make sure to sit at the bar, as they normally do when dining solo. . .

For beverages, the parent ordered the Blood orange margarita, while the individual had the Black and blue mojito. . . The margarita was quite enjoyable. . . If only the individual was not allergic to oranges. . . The mojito was still pleasant, but the parent preferred the margarita. . . The parent's drink was visually appealing, while the individual's mojito appeared somewhat lackluster. . . The individual will have to try another drink on their next visit. . .

Moving on to the food. . . The parent had to have another plate of calamari, while the individual had their sights set on dessert. . . Since they had previously raved about the banana dessert plate, they decided to order it again, especially since the manager mentioned it would be replaced in a couple of months. . . Unfortunately, their second taste of this sweet concoction could not compare to the first. . . The chocolate-dipped frozen banana slices now numbered only four, and they tasted stale and bland; the toppings were not crispy. . . The texture of the banana muffin cupcake was crumbly and tasted stale, almost as if it had been frozen and then thawed; the milkshake was uninteresting, much like a forgotten drink that is returned to, but now too far-gone and not worth consuming. . . The individual felt as though they had been dealt the short end of the stick, which was then taken back and stuck repeatedly into their eye. . . They should have taken the hint to order something else. . . It appears there was a reason this dish was being phased out. . .

The culinary experience offered a standout dish consisting of a mouth-watering tri-tip quesadilla and a tender cut of brisket.  A sweet and indulgent biscuit accompanied by a drizzle of rich honey butter was truly irresistible.  The chicken was also a notable highlight.  Conversely, a particular side dish featuring sweet potatoes and a roasted artichoke was a letdown.

A date of January 30, 2010, was noted... 

A mediocre rating of 2.5 stars was assigned. 

A visit was made to this venue while a culinary item was being prepared at a nearby market.  The establishment possessed a charming, diminutive atmosphere.  The baked goods appeared appetizing; however, upon inquiring about the standard offerings, the coffee makers became confrontational, thereby causing me to lose the pleasant, warm ambiance I had initially experienced.  The coffee beverage that was selected had a pleasing flavour.

It was a pleasant surprise when a family member I'd encountered in the Spanish capital twelve years prior paid a visit to my hometown last month.  I seized the opportunity to finally sample the offerings of a local eatery that had long been on my radar and take her there.  The evening in question fell on a Tuesday, and I was fortunate enough to stumble upon the restaurant's online menu beforehand and discover that they offer a special promotion on Tuesdays after 8 pm: a $20 bottle of wine paired with bruschetta.  Initially, I was a bit apprehensive about the noise level inside, but I was determined not to let that deter me from taking my cousin outside to the patio, especially since she had just been extolling the virtues of a city in the western United States that she had visited prior to arriving in the south-western part of the country.  

We had an extremely enjoyable time!  For the price of twenty dollars, the two of us were able to indulge in a nice bottle of Heron chardonnay and a platter of six generous bruschetta halves (featuring ricotta with dates and pistachios; smoked salmon with capers and herbs; roasted red peppers and goat cheese; and prosciutto with figs and mascarpone).  You can view our dining experience in more detail at the following link:  http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/u-SJ5QUwrNquL9VnXwl8cg?userid=M9rRM6Eo5YbKLKMG5QiIPA#oGjoq-y0BpTf_Ug6K6vmgQ.  My non-sweet-toothed relative's favorite was the peppers and goat cheese.  It was satisfying, but I have a long-standing fondness for red peppers and goat cheese, and as someone who has a pronounced sweet tooth, my number one favorite was the ricotta, dates, and pistachios.  The mascarpone and salmon were tied for second place in my book.  I am not particularly fond of prosciutto, as I find it slightly too salty, but the sweet mascarpone helped to counteract some of the saltiness.  The combination of salmon and capers was extremely tasty!  

The atmosphere was pleasant, with a palpable sense of positive energy.  Our server was efficient, friendly, and never overbearing.  The restroom was also quite charming.  My only criticism is that the interior of the restaurant was rather dimly lit.  I have made this comment before, but I will reiterate it now: I prefer to feast my eyes on the presentation of the food!  I would appreciate it if they could add more lighting.  You can view the presentation of our meal at the following link:  http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/u-SJ5QUwrNquL9VnXwl8cg?select=zsIkd6EUxXYbejAx8Srdeg#zsIkd6EUxXYbejAx8Srdeg

My family member has made me promise to take her back to this establishment (or somewhere similar) on her next visit.  If that isn't a glowing endorsement, I am at a loss to explain what would be.

I ventured out to sample the delectable cinnamon-sugar donuts at a popular eatery, hoping to snag a few of the mouthwatering pastries, complete with an assortment of donut holes.  As I had previously arrived too late, I reasoned that the third time would be the charm, only to find myself arriving too early.  Fortunately, a vendor named Pavle informed me that I had to wait for an additional 15 minutes.  In the interim, I decided to visit a nearby food truck, where I placed an order for a crepe, which typically takes 12 to 15 minutes to prepare due to the long lines of customers seeking French delicacies.  By limiting my time, I hoped to save some money; my last visit had cost me approximately $44.  Some of the vendors, however, cleverly tempted my sweet tooth, so I found myself purchasing a sample of a vendor's Espresso Almond brittle and sampling the three varieties of toffee offered by GoodyTwos - almond, dark chocolate and seasalt, and hazelnut.  I was so enamored with the toffees that I purchased two quarter-pound bags of the almond and hazelnut varieties, although I had an equal affinity for the dark chocolate one.  My current expenditure thus far?  A total of $15.  I must admit, I was somewhat apprehensive about my impending expenses.  I hastily made my way to the food truck, which would hopefully rectify my situation.

Unfortunately, I was unable to obtain a Brittany crepe today, as the vendor had run out of buckwheat honey.  The vendor, Jeff, explained that he was unaware of the vendor's whereabouts.  This was a disappointment, as I had been looking forward to trying the Brittany crepe.  I hope Jeff finds a new supplier soon; I did notice two honey vendors present this morning, but I failed to inquire about their offerings.  In the absence of the Brittany, I settled for the "My First Time" crepe, which, despite not being the one I had initially desired, was well-prepared.  I particularly enjoyed the addition of walnuts, which added a satisfying crunch to the Nutella and banana filling.  The crepe cost $5.

While waiting for my crepe, I strolled over to a nearby nut stand and sampled the roasted cinnamon almonds and cashews, as well as other varieties such as walnuts, pecans, and a spicy offering with jalapenos and "smart sugar."  I purchased a bag each of the almonds and cashews for $9.

Lastly, I had to procure my usual ration of zaatar bread and hummus from a local vendor, which cost $11, although the price of the bread has increased from $5 to $6.  My total expenditure for this Saturday morning?  A total of $40, which far surpassed my initial estimate, but I do not mind, as the money supports local businesses.  I cherish the opportunity to enjoy the beautiful weather, savor a delicious breakfast, and engage with new people during my favorite part of the day.

P.S.  I almost forgot to mention that I returned to the eatery and found a line of people waiting to purchase the freshly-made donuts, so I joined the queue.  This allowed me to observe Charleen expertly preparing the Roasted Chicken Tortas, complete with bean spread and chipotle mayo on ciabatta bread, which cost $10.  These looked so appealing that I almost wanted to purchase one for my mother to try.  Perhaps next time.  The brownies with pecans and figs, priced at $2 each, also caught my attention, although I must abstain from pecans.  Alas, this morning's excursion was quite costly.  My total expenditure, including the donuts and donut holes, now stands at $45.  I must be more frugal in the future.

It's definitely worth four stars for the fantastic happy hour deals on their menu, which features a delightful pasta dish, a dish consisting of mussels and aqua clams from Prince Edward, and a build-your-own hand-tossed pizza cooked on a hearth stone, as well as a dish called bistec del Furio.  Everything is simply excellent!  I haven't had the pleasure of dining here for dinner yet, as the service has been somewhat slow; however, I am willing to overlook a menu with a higher price point if the service is not only knowledgeable, but also attentive and extremely efficient.

A truly unforgettable theatrical experience! 4.5 out of 5 stars!

Kudos to a popular review platform for randomly selecting a lucky individual to receive complimentary tickets, thereby allowing me to finally catch a performance of a classic musical that I had been eager to see for years!  Although our seats were located at the rear of the auditorium, the expansive view of the stage was unobstructed, and the acoustics were remarkably clear and crisp tonight.  Surprisingly, the wait at the restroom was significantly longer before the show commenced than afterwards.

I thoroughly enjoyed this particular musical - the actor who portrayed the village milkman in the lead role was exceptionally funny and captivating, and the entire cast was equally impressive.  The Russian dancers were a visual treat to behold - a true highlight of the production.  It is worth noting that spectators would be wise to avoid the restroom during the wedding scene, as the mesmerizing choreography nearly prompted me to give the troupe a standing ovation!  As an individual with a considerable amount of experience attending musicals, I was pleasantly surprised to recognize that one of the musical's numbers had actually inspired a song from a different musical, which was later remade by a well-known artist in the early 2000s.  Additionally, I immediately recognized another iconic song from the musical.  The sets and costumes were also noteworthy - I wholeheartedly recommend this show to anyone!

Here's a revised version of the text, maintaining the original meaning while obscuring the author's identity and using more period marks:

It was on a particular date that I visited a store, utilizing the remaining balance on a gift card I had received. The market, which was slated to close on a specific Saturday at 5p., had already begun to show signs of exhaustion, with roughly one-third to one-half of the shelves being stocked. The deli and prepared food sections were exceptions to this trend, but even these areas were not entirely immune to the general decline. The produce aisle was almost devoid of products, and the pastry case was nearly bare. However, there were a few bottles of Arizona wine still available for purchase. Had I not adopted a preference for organic and sustainable wines a few months prior, I would have likely left with a few bottles in hand...

To satisfy my hunger, I ordered a few items, including pasta, quinoa, and sweet potato salads. I was thoroughly impressed with the quality of these dishes, particularly the lemon-herb vinaigrette used in the quinoa salad. The pasta was cooked to perfection, with a delightful texture and bite that was not overly greasy. The sweet potatoes were also exceptional, with a nice balance of flavor and texture. I had the opportunity to take a few photos of my meal, which can be viewed online at a popular review website.

In an effort to make the most of my gift card, I decided to order two sandwiches, sampling a few bites and then packaging the remainder for later consumption. I was pleased to discover that the Smoke Shop bacon used in the sandwiches was incredibly rich and flavorful, with a minimal amount of fat to trim. The aioli was also a highlight, with a delightful balance of flavors. The toasted multi-grain bread had a wonderful crunch to it, while the "Friggin' chicken" sandwich was a standout due to its spicy kick, which was tempered by the sweetness of the mango chutney and the richness of the cheese. The bun was also a highlight, with a perfect balance of texture and flavor.

However, I did find the a la carte pricing to be somewhat steep. Nevertheless, knowing that the store sources its products locally and often uses organic ingredients did help to alleviate some of my concerns.

Although the store's grocery and wine bar is closing, the Wednesday night and Saturday morning markets will continue to operate. Unfortunately, the crowd that was present on this particular evening was somewhat sparse, which may have been due in part to a sudden thunderstorm that had passed through the area just prior to my arrival. However, it seemed as though those who were there were there out of a sense of obligation rather than enthusiasm.

Addendum: On a later date, I decided to try two products from a local ranch, namely their goats' milk caramel fudge sauce and goats' milk caramel sauce. These items were reasonably priced, especially considering the store's 25% off sale. I plan to use these products as dips and ice cream toppings, as well as for other creative applications. I have since tried the caramel sauce on its own, paired with banana, and I must say that it is absolutely delightful. The caramel flavor is exquisite, with a silky texture and a subtle scent of goats' milk in the background. Unless one has a strong aversion to goats' milk, I believe that both novices and enthusiasts of goats' milk products will enjoy this caramel offering.

On September 2, 2010, I had the pleasure of dining at a renowned establishment, whose name I shall refrain from mentioning.  The eatery in question boasts a history of several dining experiences, many of which have unfortunately ceased to exist (notably, Latitude 30 and The Phantom Horse Grill).  Its Lobby Grill is a scaled-down version of the latter, featuring identical furnishings in a different setting.  Alas, I would have dined there sooner if I could have located it more expeditiouslysimply follow the signs until they appear to be leading you astray, and you will be nearly there!  Do not be deterred by the apparent scarcity of parking spaces; the truth is that they are situated just around the corner, situated at the base of a gentle incline.

Initially, there was a minor commotion, as it seemed that the main dining area was closed, with seating available only at the bar.  Fortunately, the host was kind enough to accommodate our request to sit in a booth; this was a welcome respite, as the bar area appeared chilly and dimly lit, whereas the main room was warm and radiant.  The service was somewhat sluggish, despite the fact that there were only three diners seated prior to us, including a toddler, and I had perused the menu online in advancethus, I was well-prepared to place my order.  (Oh, how I look forward to the day when I can submit my order online, and it will be ready for me upon my arrival!)

We ordered the Filet Bleu Cheese Pizza and the Reinvented Waldorf Salad.  Regrettably, it took approximately 35 to 40 minutes for our order to arrive, so it would be advisable to bring a book or engage in conversation with your companions, lest you find yourself with an extended wait.  Happily, there is a gift shop conveniently situated across the corridor!  As far as resort gift shops go, this one is quite respectable.  It even carries a selection of Brighton jewelry!  Be aware, however, that their inventory does not include the latest items you would typically find at a mall.  But I digress...

I have included the prices of our entrees, which, I must confess, were somewhat steep.  Nevertheless, when my mother is willing to overlook the higher costs to indulge in another slice of that delectable pizza, replete with tender chunks of filet and pungent Bleu cheese (we managed to consume nearly the entire pie, save for a small slice, which I took home and savored for dinner that evening!), or the exceptional salad (the candied walnuts were absolutely irresistible!), then I know that I have discovered a true gem of a dining establishment.

We shall return very soon!

There exists a notable, large-scale event in the Asian community that is currently underway.

I accompanied a family member to a different location today, only to discover that an Asian festival was taking place.  It appears that such events featuring Asian crafts and jewelry are relatively common in this particular area.  My family member was visibly delighted, as they have a strong affinity for shopping and negotiating prices, and negotiating is a common practice in cities across Asia; thus, they felt completely at ease in this setting.  Conversely, I found the experience to be thoroughly underwhelming.  I chose to take a leisurely walk while my family member continued shopping; I eventually came across a few food vendors, and, as it so happens, one of them was called "Hey Joe."  We had eaten a substantial breakfast just prior, so that particular option was not particularly appealing to me.  I did locate a food truck selling Maui Shave Ice, but that is a topic for another review...

We did eventually visit the complimentary glass exhibit, and it was well worth the trip from North Scottsdale to Mesa.  I have uploaded a few photographs that I took and hope that you will find them enjoyable.  I intend to return soon and attend a few live performances.

A subpar happy hour sushi experience left a sour taste in my mouth.  I stopped by on the twentieth of the month, a full twelve months after my initial visit.  The same two culinary specialists, a pair of individuals whose names start with the letters 'J' and 'R', were still at the helm, as was the restaurant's manager, a gentleman with the moniker 'L'.  I brought my dietary restrictions to their attention and ordered a trio of dishes: spicy tuna ($4.50), spicy salmon ($4.50), and a soft-shelled crab roll ($7.95).  The first two items were prepared by the 'J' specialist, while the 'R' specialist was tasked with crafting the crab roll.  I was fortunate enough to inquire about the 'R' specialist's plan to replace a certain ingredient.  He informed me that he could substitute it with radishes and yamagobo, a type of pickled burdock root that bears a striking resemblance to julienned carrots.  Had I remained silent, I may have been left disappointed, much like I was with the other two rolls.  The tuna and salmon were essentially just rice and a mashed fish filling.  I managed to finish a few pieces of each dish, but ultimately gave up.  (I was, after all, famished.)  I packed the leftovers and decided to speak with the manager, who graciously offered to comp one of the dishes.  Fair enough, considering I had consumed the equivalent of one dish.  If I were to return for happy hour in the future, I would likely stick to two rolls: the dependable soft-shelled crab roll, which is wrapped in nori, then rice, and then with an omelet, thinly sliced.  It was a delightful experience.  

Since I did not enjoy the other two sushi rolls, I opted to replace them with a rainbow roll ($8.95), which originally consists of salmon, yellowtail, tuna, and shrimp, with avocado and cucumber.  However, my version was lacking certain components, but still managed to be quite tasty, and more visually appealing, and more texturally satisfying than the mashed disasters that were the salmon and tuna sushi.

It is unlikely that I will be returning anytime soon for happy hour.  Indeed, I have discovered a new happy hour sushi destination... Sushi 101 in Tempe!

On two separate occasions, August 25th and December 16th, I had the pleasure of dining at a certain eatery.  On August 25th, a special happy hour menu offered a refreshing glass of white wine cooler for $4 and a delectable prosciutto platter for $7 or $8.  The wine cooler, expertly crafted right before my eyes, was savored in mere moments.  It was a delightful experience!  The prosciutto platter was satisfactory, but the accompanying cheese was truly the highlight; I made a mental note to try more cheese-based dishes in the future.  Unfortunately, the peppers were not to my liking due to a sensitivity I possess.  The breadsticks, on the other hand, were a hit, and I wished there were more of them.

The Pub Burger, which I indulged in on December 16th, was a culinary masterpiece!  It featured a delightful combination of havarti cheese, thick-cut bacon, and a tangy BBQ sauce, all nestled within a sesame-topped pretzel bun...  It was a truly unforgettable experience, reminiscent of a memorable scene from a popular film.  Unfortunately, the accompanying fries were a letdown, but my server quickly rectified the situation by providing a fresh batch, although they too were somewhat soggy.
