I would have liked to award this establishment four stars, but my last visit was marred by a cacophony of noise that necessitated the retrieval of my earbuds.  The music playing in the background was enjoyable, but the volume was overwhelming.  My server kindly agreed to adjust the volume, but it wasn't until halfway through my meal that the noise level became more manageable.  I also attempted to order a cocktail, but ironically, my server was unable to hear me!  In the end, I was thoroughly satisfied with my meal, and I left feeling content, ready to enjoy a great movie at the cinema ("Black Swan" is a must-see, by the way!).

A commendable cinema indeed boasts a spacious seating arrangement.  Its well-maintained facilities, including ample lighting, are certainly a plus.  However, the women's restroom at this particular establishment was unfortunately plagued by a persistent odor.  My family and I recently had the pleasure of attending a couple of 3D screenings here, namely "How to Train Your Dragon" and "Alice in Wonderland", both of which were thoroughly enjoyable and a delight to watch, with the voice acting perfectly synchronised with the characters.  

It is indeed puzzling that the technology behind 3D movie projection has not yet reached a state of perfection.  We had initially planned to watch "Clash of the Titans" but were unable to do so after 20 minutes of technical difficulties, despite the staff's best efforts to rectify the issue.  Consequently, the management offered complimentary passes to all attendees, which was a welcome gesture, especially considering the commotion caused by some patrons demanding free snacks.  Free food items?  It is hardly a reasonable expectation, considering that they only cost a mere $5.  Patience and understanding are often rewarded with complimentary movie tickets, even for 3D screenings, which typically cost $13.75 at this cinema.  I have had similar experiences at another cinema, AZ Mills Harkins 3D IMAX, where the movie failed to start correctly.  In that instance, I also received complimentary movie passes.  It is indeed amusing that some people would demand free food items, equating them to expensive drink coupons. 

Incidentally, the 3D experience at this cinema, specifically at Westgate, is significantly better than that at Harkins, possibly due to the engaging nature of the films we watched last night.  In contrast, my experience with "Avatar 3D" in Dolby 3D at Harkins was underwhelming, especially when compared to the 3D IMAX version I had seen at AZ Mills.  I will need to conduct further research to determine the reasons behind this disparity.

It has been a couple of weeks since I stopped by a certain eatery, and I must admit that I still feel somewhat duped.  What I truly craved was their hazelnut royale pastry, but the price tag- a staggering $6 per item- was far beyond my budget.  After a brief interlude, the male proprietor persuaded me to try their croissant.  Following a short wait, he warmed it up in the microwave, then proceeded to charge me $8, plus applicable taxes, which I deemed excessive, especially given the fact that the croissant was nearly a day old.  I had been expecting a crisper texture, but due to the microwaving, the bottom layer was extremely soggy, while only the outermost layers were marginally crispy.  As I perused the take-out menu, I was unable to locate the croissant under the dinner section; instead, I discovered it listed under the breakfast menu- $5.95 with a white sauce, and $6.55 with scrambled eggs.  Consequently, I was charged $8 for a plain ham and cheese croissant that was, in all likelihood, a leftover from the breakfast menu??  

I left that dining establishment feeling thoroughly disenchanted with my dinner selection, and, given the rising prices, I do not foresee myself returning anytime soon, if ever.

On October twenty-first, twenty-twelve, I made the mistake of ordering a large Popeye pizza from a local establishment for takeout.  The pizza, which I have included a link to a photograph of on a popular review website, was, unfortunately, a complete disaster  the worst I have had in recent weeks, and the worst I have had from this particular restaurant since I started dining there two years ago.  It was a peculiar coincidence that I had not noticed until after reviewing my past reviews, but this visit marked a date exactly two years from the day I first set foot in this eatery.  Having just finished work, I telephoned the restaurant to place my order, and was told that it would be ready in twenty minutes, so I stopped by a nearby pharmacy to return some unused merchandise.  By the time I arrived, it was probably closer to thirty minutes since I had gotten off the phone.  A young man whom I had previously seen make an error with an order handed me the pizza box and informed me that he had prepared it himself, which seemed unusual, given that I only knew him to operate the cash register, answer the phone, or retrieve orders and entrees from the back.  As is usually the case, the person who handed me my pizzas typically shows me the finished product before I pay for it, so he opened the box, and I simply took note of the spinach and the ricotta and expressed my hope that his creation tasted as good as it looked.

As soon as I arrived home, I tore into the box, and from the first bite, I knew that this was a subpar product.  Several months ago, I started to request "light on the mozzarella and heavy on the ricotta," but tonight I forgot to specify this, so I was delighted to find that this pizza had a considerable amount of ricotta on it.  However, the mozzarella and the goat cheese were completely absent from this product!  There was, however, an overwhelming amount of garlic.  If you examine the photograph included, you will see that there is a substantial amount on the pizza and on the box that had fallen off of the two slices I popped into the toaster oven, and I assure you that there were plenty on those slices.  It was quite obnoxious, but I persevered and ate the garlic pieces, which were much thicker than normal.  I am aware that garlic is beneficial for one's health, and I am still recovering from a recent upper respiratory infection, so I decided to overlook this oversight tonight.  Unfortunately, I was unable to ignore how awful it was the following night, as the pizza tasted even worse (very bland), so much so that I was unable to enjoy the rest of it.  It is very important to note that on both nights I consumed this pizza, I also suffered from headaches.  I have never suffered from headaches after eating pizzas from this restaurant before, so this was also unpleasing.  I wondered if the new person added something to the pie.  I wondered why he even prepared the pie himself, and not the regular chef?  If no one was able to create and bake a pizza worthy of this restaurant's reputation, of which I have testified to in my reviews and by word-of-mouth, why not just inform me on the phone?  I could have ordered something else.  I could have spent twenty-five dollars (including tip) on other entrees and not on this disastrous Popeye interpretation...

I am truly sorry not to be able to partake in the pizzas, calzones, and chicken fettuccine Alfredo entrees from this restaurant in the future anymore, since I now cannot trust the quality and presentation of the products served here, but I thank this establishment for the great pizzas my mother, other relatives, and I did have in the past.

UPDATE: 

I have revised my rating from 5 stars to 4 stars after recalling a particular culinary shortcoming.  A certain family member and I are aficionados of a specific seafood delicacy, which we consistently seek out at various dining establishments.  We are particularly fond of a certain type of batter coating on our seafood of choice - one that is light and crispy, regardless of whether it is made from panko, flour, or breadcrumbs.  Typically, I enjoy my preferred dish with a light drizzle of lemon juice.  Despite having given a local eatery two opportunities to impress us (after initially forgetting that we had previously tried it), the calamari was unfortunately overpowered by a thick, doughy batter on both occasions.

This restaurant, which has two locations, is a well-regarded Italian dining option.  From Mondays through Fridays, it offers a daily express lunch special for $6.95, which features a different selection each day.  I particularly appreciate their baked stuffed shells and chicken cutlet piccata, as well as their early bird special, which is also available during lunch under a different name, between 4p-5p.  During this time, customers can choose from a variety of pasta, sauce, and toppings (vegetarian options are plentiful), accompanied by a superior antipasto salad and ciabatta bread.  I also appreciate the availability of whole wheat spaghetti.

My preferred dishes at this establishment include the cannelloni, jumbo stuffed shells, chicken piccata, and the alfredo and marinara sauces.  Their apple bread pudding, served with a rich Frangelico caramel sauce, is also a standout.

On a particular date, 27th of May, I decided to pay a visit to a popular dining spot known as Hillside.  Notwithstanding the fact that the line was still substantial, despite the hour being around 10:30-10:45 on a Thursday morning, I also observed that this establishment was quite noisy.  I did not find the din inside the premises tolerable, even though the weather outside was warm and sunny, and apparently a few patrons shared my sentiments, as the only available tables without umbrellas were scarce.  Had it not been for the cacophony, I would have given this eatery a rating of four or more stars.  However, I was relieved to discover that one of the staff members was willing to set up a table with an umbrella, provided one simply requested it.

Prior to my visit, I had perused the menu online, so I was somewhat familiar with the items they offered.  Due to the crowded conditions and the overwhelming noise that greeted me on my first visit, which startled me and left me searching for some respite, I was unable to inspect the display cases and countertops, which featured a variety of pastries, including cupcakes, apple pie by the slice, cookies, tarts, muffins, and scones, all of which change daily.  I would strongly advise others to take a look at these baked goods.  (The apple pie is truly exceptional!)  The daily special seemed appealing, but I opted to try the Croque Madame, a variation of the Croque Monsieur topped with a fried egg, and the Pancakes with Apple Compote.  The ordering process takes place at the counter, where one pays and receives a card to mark one's table.  It takes some time for the food to be prepared, so it is advisable to take this into account when planning a visit.  This would be an opportune time to peruse the pastries, but depending on the level of busyness at Hillside, it may be wise to place all of one's order selections at the beginning and have it ready for pickup.

The Croque Madame was truly outstanding, albeit with a few burnt bits.  The French bread, which I believe was sourced from MJ Bread, was perfectly suited, topped with an excellent bechamel sauce, sliced ham, melted Gruyre cheese, and a fried egg!  This is definitely an item that I would order repeatedly.

The pancakes were satisfactory (I enjoyed the batter mix!), but the apple compote was not to my liking.  I will admit that the compotes I have had previously were fruit reductions that were thick and sweetened from the natural juices, as well as added sugar, so perhaps Hillside's "apple compote" technically qualifies as a compote (as defined by dictionary.com- "fruit stewed or cooked in a syrup"), but I found the topping to be neither sweet nor stewed enough (the chopped apples still had a lot of crunch in them!).  Fortunately, I had a bottle of pure maple syrup in my handbag to sweeten the pancakes!

On a later date, 24th of July, I revisited Hillside in early June and sampled the berry pancakes with homemade whipped cream.  These were delightful!  I almost devoured the entire dish, and had I not tried the apple pie, I would have finished it off completely.  The added bananas (which were perfectly ripened) elevated this dish to new heights!

The building itself appeared to be aesthetically pleasing from the exterior, with an added bonus of offering scenic views of a man-made lake situated nearby.  I found the surrounding park, where this particular branch is located, to be a lovely place for leisurely strolls.  Unfortunately, my experiences with the library were not quite as idyllic.  Upon multiple visits, I found that the location was either inaccessible or overrun with noisy young individuals, coupled with the presence of people of all ages who engaged in loud conversations on their mobile phones.  The computer section was consistently overcrowded, making it challenging to secure a seat or find an empty table free from personal belongings left behind by absent-minded patrons.  In reality, the atmosphere inside the library bore a striking resemblance to a bustling coffee shop, particularly given the section where one could purchase coffee and pastries.  

The library did, however, offer a considerable collection of CDs, DVDs, and books-on-DVDs, which allowed patrons to place holds both in-person and online, and the notification system for availability was relatively prompt.  Nonetheless, I ceased using these services after discovering that the items I borrowed carried an unpleasant odour, likely due to the fact that many users handled them with their armpits while walking back to the library, a common practice that becomes more pronounced in desert environments where the heat and humidity can be oppressive.  Despite repeated cleaning and sanitizing efforts, the odour persisted.  I am not exaggerating when I say that this was a thoroughly unpleasant experience.  To confirm my assertion, I suggest you try handling a DVD or book on your next visit and take a sniff.  You have been warned!

While the surrounding park does offer serene and invigorating walks with picturesque views, there are other attractions to explore.  Visitors can also enjoy a playground or two located on the opposite side of the park, as well as picnic areas equipped with grills and tables.  Fishing is also an option, although it is essential to note that the lakes are contaminated with toxins and algae, as indicated by warning signs, and I have personally observed a disturbing number of dead small animals floating on the water's surface.  If you plan to explore the entire park, it is advisable to have a companion or two accompany you, especially around sunset, as there is a specific location with a single entry and exit point, which could pose a safety risk in the event of malicious intent.

It is undeniable that the atmosphere of this establishment is an opulent feast for both the senses of sight and touch.  However, the steep price one pays for such exclusivity is quite substantial.  As I sat in the lobby, waiting to be seated at the sushi counter, which opened for dinner service at 5:30 p.m., I couldn't help but notice a rather distressing lack of attention to detail.  Specifically, the coffee table situated adjacent to the sushi restaurant's host desk, which is presumably under the purview of the venue's housekeeping staff, remained littered with remnants of food.  This oversight was particularly striking, given that a representative did make an appearance to inform me about the bar menu that had been left on the table and inquired if I required any items from the bar; it is reasonable to assume that this staff member would have noticed the state of the table.  I ordered a $9.50 soft-shelled crab roll, a $10 veggie tempura appetizer, and a $19 baked lobster roll, all of which were available at 50% off during the establishment's one-year anniversary celebration.  While all of these dishes were satisfactory, taking into account the lavish ambiance, I would be willing to pay $9.50 for the soft-shelled crab roll.  However, I would draw the line at the other two items, even with the 50% discount.  The lobster roll, which consisted of five pieces, was indeed delectable, and the cream sauce was exquisite; nonetheless, for a price of $19, I expect a dining experience akin to that depicted in films such as "The Ugly Truth" or "When Harry Met Sally."  If one has the financial means or is fortunate enough to have someone else covering the bill, then this sushi establishment near Old Town Scottsdale is an option worth considering.

A visually appealing storefront!  It is as if I have temporarily escaped to a tropical paradise, thanks to the lush foliage of trees, shrubs, and flowers.  This brief, yet pleasant, experience is a lovely surprise, a delightful treat in itself.  :)  The usual items on display are not present at the moment, as the staff has brought out their seasonal offerings.  A variety of charming pastel-hued and foil-wrapped bunnies (both milk and dark chocolate), tiny eggs, larger eggs, both hollow and filled, jelly beans, pastel-colored truffles, and beautifully decorated eggs are available for selection.  I was disappointed to learn that the small chocolate bunnies (priced at $1.15) only come in milk chocolate, but I was informed that they are also available in medium- and large-sized chocolate rabbits (priced at $5.65 and $9.70, respectively).

Upon entering, I had intended to purchase 13 candy bars in both milk and dark chocolate, and I left with those items plus three additional mini-chocolate milk bunnies.  [Silence!  The dark chocolate bars with almonds are reserved for me!]  :D

As an aside, it is worth noting that a well-known tradition of this establishment is to offer complimentary samples to all customers.  What is less well-known, however, is that the sales staff are typically given two or three truffle options to choose from, which means the sample you receive may differ from the one the person in front of you was given.  My surprise free sample today was a rich dark chocolate bordeaux, paired with a brown sugar buttercream.  I have not yet had the pleasure of tasting it...  I wonder if this company will ever consider replacing the corn syrup in some of their products with pure cane sugar in the future.  Only time will tell.

A certain high-end beauty product caught my eye at a popular beauty retailer a couple of weeks ago; it was the $28 Dior Addict (Stiletto, a name that conveys a sense of allure and danger, reminiscent of a certain 90s film).  I had been eyeing this product at Sephora, so I decided to visit two department stores that carry the brand to see if they were offering a complimentary gift with purchase.  Unfortunately, the promotion was not available until September, so I had to make do with what I found.  My first and last stop that day was Macy's, due to time constraints, the service I received, and the fact that the sales associate at the Dior counter quoted me a lower price for the lipsticks I was interested in purchasing.  I was planning to buy at least two shades (Stiletto and Envy), as well as explore the $30 Rouge Dior colors and the $34 Serum Rouge selections.  Given my aversion to returning defective products, I decided to sample some of the testers using the disposable brushes provided for customers.  However, a woman soon positioned herself behind and to the right of me, where I could see her, and despite my friendly greeting, I began to feel increasingly uncomfortable, so I decided to stick to my initial choices, as I could always return if I wanted to try more products. 

The sales associate rang up my purchases, and the total was higher than I had anticipated.  I inquired about the discrepancy, and she explained that she had mistakenly looked at the price tag of another product when I had asked her about the price earlier.  Although the difference was minimal, I decided to let it slide, and I left the store. 

A few days later, I returned to Sephora to restock on a specific brand of lipsticks that I adore.  I typically purchase three or more of these at a time to replace the ones that have already fallen victim to the harsh Arizona climate and broken off.  I do not have the patience or the time to save these broken pieces and apply them with lipstick brushes; I wish I did, as it would allow me to allocate more funds to my other hobbies, such as dining out and watching movies at a local theater.  In the end, I ended up buying five colors, which came out to around $77, including tax (three for myself, and two to gift to my mother, because I like her). 

I must say, Macy's, that if you hadn't made me feel like a suspicious individual by sending a guard to watch me, I would have spent a significant amount more on my favorite beauty products at your counters, rather than at other stores.  I am not even dwelling on how the sales associate misled me by quoting the wrong price, when I had specifically given her the product's line and color to look up.  Never mind.  I have made a conscious decision to boycott this particular location.  Should I ever want to make a purchase from Macy's in the future, I will either go to a different store or travel to another state.  Perhaps I will simply spend my money at Dillard's and Sephora.

I must extend my heartfelt gratitude to the proprietors of a quaint little eatery, situated in a charming part of town, for providing me with a brief respite from my current state of unwellness.  As I sat down to enjoy my meal, I felt an overwhelming sense of excitement and anticipation, which momentarily distracted me from my less-than-stellar appearance, clad in a pair of yoga pants, a Life is Good tee, a hooded zip pullover, and a pair of glasses.  It was a pleasant surprise to find the establishment bustling with activity - I had never seen it so crowded, and to my astonishment, there was a queue of patrons waiting to place their orders!  Due to the fact that the majority of the tables were occupied indoors, the atmosphere was quite lively, so I seized the opportunity to conceal my, shall we say, less-than-ideal health from the discerning crowd and dine outdoors.  However, before I could indulge in my meal, I had to place my order.

Having perused the menu online beforehand, I had already made up my mind to order the French toast, minus the powdered sugar, as is my usual preference.  Nevertheless, I was tempted to try something new, and the basic breakfast option, consisting of eggs, toast, jam, and fruit, caught my eye.  I was also considering either a smoothie or an elixir, but the menu indicated that I would need to ask for the elixir menu to view the options.  Unfortunately, there was only one available, and it seemed to be a concoction specifically designed for females, which I didn't require, thank you very much.  ("Not that there's anything wrong with that.")  I managed to save $8 by not ordering it.  The smoothie I had my heart set on contained pomegranate juice, which I suspected might contain some unwanted ingredients, and sure enough, I spotted grape seed oil extract on the juice bottles near the cash register.  Good for me that I was able to avoid it, and I saved $8 as a result.  Lastly, I ordered a cappuccino (from a reputable coffee cart) and a glass of water without cucumber.  I explicitly requested that my French toast be made without powdered sugar, and was informed that it would take approximately twenty to twenty-five minutes to prepare, as they had run out of bread and the next batch was in the oven.  I was more than willing to wait, and besides, I was also looking forward to trying the Kamut toast and almond butter.  As I paid for my three items, I was told that my food would be ready in about thirty minutes, which caught me off guard, but I was in no mood to make a fuss, especially when I needed to secure an empty table before someone else snatched it!

I managed to find an outdoor table, but it needed to be bussed first.  No problem, as I was assisted by a shy and endearing associate.  One thing I appreciate about frequenting establishments that cater to vegans, vegetarians, and those with gluten intolerance is that the staff members are often humble and good-natured.  Another thing I enjoy is the unique, eclectic, and fun atmosphere that these places typically have, with their colorful curtains, brightly-painted tables and chairs, and whimsical dinnerware.  The outdoor seating area had a mosaic two-top table with mismatched chairs - I sat on the one without any food residue on its seat.

My food arrived sooner than expected, and the cappuccino and glass of water, served in a lidless canning jar, took a few minutes to arrive.  It was about ten minutes after I started sipping my coffee that the Banana bread French toast arrived, but, much to my dismay, it was sprinkled with powdered sugar!  However, the staff member, Russell, promptly took it back and brought me a new one.  What exceptional service!  The Kamut toast, almond butter, jam, and fruit plate, however, remained untouched, so I was pleased.  Still content, even when I discovered that the almond butter was of the raw variety - I'm not particularly fond of its flavor, or lack thereof, and I usually prefer the roasted kind.  Fortunately, I am not allergic to chia, sesame, or sunflower seeds, as they were present on the dish, and they added a much-needed flavor to the bland-tasting almond butter.  The varied textures on this dish also provided my mouth with something to be happy about!  The Banana bread French toast arrived about five minutes later, and what a marvel that was!  The French toast had the perfect crunch on the outside, a gorgeous pound-cake-meets-angel-cake consistency on the inside, and a wonderful roasted-banana scent that soon delighted my taste buds!

It was on March 31, 2011, that I found myself in a predicament.  I had originally intended to partake in a certain establishment's happy hour, as I possessed a gift card, but upon arriving, I discovered an inordinate number of patrons at the bar, and the prospect of sitting outside in the sweltering heat was unappealing.  I had, however, heard that another restaurant, which I shall refer to as "Restaurant X", offered a similar happy hour promotion, complete with complimentary edamame and other enticing offerings.  Thus, I resigned myself to dining at Restaurant X, where I opted for their signature salad, the Waimanolo.  To my surprise, I discovered that Restaurant X had expanded its happy hour menu to include not only edamame, but also ahi tuna, calamari, Wagyu sliders, and beef skewers, all of which could be paired with a selection of wines by the glass and the restaurant's signature cocktails for a mere $5 each!  While I had previously been underwhelmed by the skewers, I was drawn to the calamari, but ultimately decided to order the Wagyu beef sliders, which came with caramelized onions and sweet potato fries.  I also ordered a glass of chardonnay, but then changed my mind and opted for one of the restaurant's signature cocktails, the Fred and Ginger, instead.  This drink, which consisted of Hennessy VS cognac and Domaine du Canton ginger liqueur, garnished with a candied ginger peel, was nothing short of exquisite.  Unfortunately, I was unable to finish the entire drink, as I had to save room for the sliders and fries.  The sliders were a revelation - two of them, served on either side of a miniature Chinese takeout box filled with crispy sweet potato fries, and each bite was reminiscent of a Whopper from a bygone era, elevated to new heights by the crispy, chewy pretzel buns.  The fries, seasoned with herbs and topped with a drizzle of cheese, were the perfect accompaniment to the sliders.  In short, the cocktail and app were a steal at $5 each, and I would highly recommend them.

I must admit that I was tempted to keep this happy hour secret to myself, but I shall resist the urge and share my experience with others.  In retrospect, the cocktail and app would have been sufficient to satisfy my cravings for the rest of the day, but I was determined to stay and try more of the restaurant's offerings.  I decided to try their Chocolate souffl, a dessert that is baked to order and takes approximately 20 minutes to prepare.  While the outer edges of the chocolate cake were delightful, with a texture reminiscent of a freshly baked brownie, the lava center was rich and gooey, but the accompanying vanilla ice cream was a letdown.  The ice cream lacked a creamy texture and a strong vanilla flavor, which was a shame, considering the price of the dessert.  In the end, I felt that the dessert was overpriced and not worth the cost.

A certain resort's coffee venue, situated within its premises, serves a variety of specialty coffees and frozen beverages under the Peet's Coffee brand, in addition to freshly baked pastries.  I opted for a medium-sized iced latte ($3.70 plus applicable tax), which was prepared unsweetened but allowed for customization with sugar or two distinct syrups: Caramel or White Chocolate Mocha.  I also ordered a brown sugar and cinnamon scone ($3.75 plus applicable tax), which proved to be a delightful combination of sweet and moist.  Both items were served on separate vessels that matched the colour scheme of the gaming floor - the scone was placed on a disposable, yet tastefully designed plastic dessert plate, while the coffee was served in a stylishly designed plastic glass accompanied by a blue straw.  Although the coffee shop had only recently opened, it did not have sufficient to-go containers for the scone; however, a representative from Peet's managed to find a suitable alternative - a plastic bag that the dessert plate had been packaged in.  The representative asked if this would be acceptable, and I was about to place the scone in the bag when they kindly offered to let me take the plate as well.  As a result, I not only enjoyed a satisfying iced coffee and a pleasant scone, but I also acquired a reusable souvenir.

The service counter was immaculately maintained, with the attendant behind it being a pleasant sight: a well-groomed individual who radiated friendliness and communicated effectively.  The store's location within the shopping center was particularly convenient.  I was thoroughly pleased!!.

The current promotions were as follows: "Purchase three items, receive two for free; purchase two items, receive one for free; and purchase one item, receive the second item at half price."  Unfortunately, I failed to discover that the preferred fragrance of the gift recipient was also available in a larger bath gel size, initially priced at $15.  Nevertheless, I was able to procure the body butter and matching shower gel, along with a complementary bath glycerin soap, for $20.  A closer inspection of the available options revealed that, with the current deal, I could have acquired two body butters for $36 ($18 each) and received the jumbo bath gel at no additional cost.  However, I opted to forego this opportunity, as the gift recipient can take the bath soap on a future trip and avoid the risk of spills, which ultimately worked out in our favor.  :)

I accompanied a family member to a local establishment to indulge in sweet treats prior to attending the evening's First Friday Artwalk.  My enthusiasm for the rosemary shortbread was intense; I wished I had acquired a greater quantity of it, as I purchased only a single square.  We were also extremely impressed by the brownie chunk cookie.  I plan to return to this location during my next artwalk.

Upon perusing a particular eatery's advertisement in March, my companion and I found ourselves reminiscing about a culinary experience we had been yearning to relish.  Alas, our gastronomical desires were thwarted at the time due to a prior dining engagement with pho; thus, we had to postpone our visit until our next shopping excursion brought us to that vicinity once more.  Upon meeting the proprietors, we were warmly welcomed by their hospitality, and we wished them great success in their endeavours.

As it was nearing closing time, the offerings at the buffet table were limited, and the options available did not particularly pique our interest.  Consequently, we decided to order the pork skewers, a dish of which the husband and wife duo took great pride in crafting.  Additionally, we opted for the liempo, a serving of which our companion had been eyeing.  A combination plate consisting of these two items was served with a side of rice and achara (pickled papaya and carrots).  I also ordered a piece of saba at langka, which comprised saba bananas (or plantains) and jackfruit, wrapped in lumpia wrapper and deep-fried.

The wait for our food was somewhat longer than anticipated, but our time was not entirely wasted, as my companion spent a considerable amount of time procuring groceries.  However, the delay was more than justified, for the meal that finally arrived was truly exceptional.  The pork barbecue skewers were a culinary delight, transporting me back to my childhood days in a distant land, where street food vendors offered a diverse array of delectable dishes, including barbecue, fried fishballs, steamed rice rolls, and tuber pancakes, all accompanied by an assortment of sauces.  As I reminisced about those pork skewers, I found myself yearning to return to that eatery, rather than indulging in the Italian or French cuisine I had initially contemplated.  The liempo, on the other hand, was somewhat underwhelming, and I could have done without it; the pork belly pieces, although edible, failed to match the flavour profile of the skewers.  My companion, however, enjoyed the liempo, but concurred that the barbecue was the true highlight of the meal, and the proprietors indeed had a culinary gem to be proud of.

It is worth noting that the dessert, although not entirely forgettable, was somewhat of a letdown.  Firstly, the presentation was unimpressive.  Secondly, the sweetness level was lacking, and the turon rested on a pool of caramel sauce that I failed to leave even a single drop of on my plate.  Not because the dessert was delectable, but because it required a more pronounced sweetness.  My companion had foreseen this outcome, and after sampling the dessert, she quipped that she should have simply purchased the ingredients and prepared it at home.  I couldn't agree more, dear companion!

On July 28th, 2012, I encountered a group of acquaintances who had begun imbibing during the happy hour period (which, incidentally, was scheduled to commence at 5:30 p.m.).  I arrived around 8:40 p.m., fortunately stumbling upon a convenient parking spot in close proximity to the entrance.  As I entered, I was immediately struck by the cacophony of noise emanating from the patrons, and the pungent aroma of stale beer wafting through the air was nothing short of overwhelming.  Although I was initially inclined to depart, I had previously notified my friends of my arrival via text message and Yelp check-in, thus rendering an immediate exit impossible.  Upon locating my companions at a four-seat table, I endeavored to greet them warmly, only to be forced to raise my voice in an attempt to be heard  a situation that I found thoroughly exasperating.  The fact that I had to lean in close to their mouth to discern their words only served to exacerbate my discomfort, and I found myself nostalgically reminiscing about a more tranquil experience at Four Peaks, where I could have been sipping on a chilled glass of Peach ale while awaiting the arrival of my meal.

I remained seated at that table for a period of twenty minutes, observing as no fewer than three servers traversed the area without inquiring whether I required any assistance.  Thankfully, I had brought my own bottle of water, which proved to be a lifesaver, as the din and commotion were not only causing my head and ears to ache but also leaving me feeling famished and parched.  It wasn't until approximately thirty minutes had elapsed, and I was standing near a landing of stairs alongside two other companions, that a server finally approached to inquire if I had been attended to.  By that point, I had already made up my mind to depart and was in the process of bidding farewell to my friends.

Regrettably, I failed to receive the service I had hoped for.  Beer samplers, measuring 3 ounces, were available for either $1 or $2 (designated by a plus sign).  This would have been an intriguing way to sample various beers and gauge the servers' knowledge of their offerings  a novelty that I, as a novice in the world of beers, was eager to explore, but one that I soon discovered I was not particularly fond of due to the prevalence of hops.  Pints were priced at $5 each, while pitchers were available for $9  a sum that, although steep, was still a more attractive option.  Furthermore, I was under the impression that the establishment would feature a diverse selection of O.H.S.O. brewery beers, but I was only able to spot two.  However, given the lack of service I received, this information was rendered largely inconsequential.

It's been nearly a year since our last visit to a Mediterranean eatery in a coastal town.  The braised lamb dishes served here are truly exceptional, and they're often accompanied by a side of brown rice adorned with toasted nuts.  My dining companion never requires any persuasion to dine at this establishment.  We both have a soft spot for the creamy tomato soup, which is simply divine; unfortunately, I've had to abstain from it for the past couple of years due to dietary restrictions.  The hummus has consistently met our expectations, and we appreciate the presentation, which features sliced tomatoes and a few pickled cornichons.  We always request warm, toasted flatbread.  Upon reviewing recent reviews, I wonder if the kitchen has started using subpar ingredients?

The skewered chicken is also quite flavorful, but the braised lamb dishes are the true standout.  It's worth giving them a try.  As for dessert, we've found it to be somewhat underwhelming.  I do have two major grievances: This eatery consistently emits a strong, chemical-like odor; every time we've dined there, the scent has been overpowering.  It's a major turn-off.  Additionally, the service from the older gentleman has been consistently brusque.  Initially, I attributed it to a cultural difference, but now I believe he may simply be unhappy in his role.

The dining area could benefit from a design refresh, particularly the counter area.  As we last visited, the entrance hallway looked more like a drab office space than a welcoming area for customers to wait and admire the dessert display.  On a more positive note, the women's restroom was always spotless during my visits.

I have dined at this establishment on a couple of occasions previously.  The initial visit, which took place roughly two years ago, involved ordering the chicken shawarma entree, which was accompanied by pickled vegetables, hummus, garlic sauce, and pita.  Unfortunately, a considerable number of the chicken pieces were still raw, rendering them nearly impossible to chew, and some were still visibly blood-red.  When I brought this to the attention of my server, he reacted as if I was the first person to ever voice a complaint about the food at this eatery.  He departed and returned with an individual I assumed to be the chef, who displayed even greater offense at my suggestion that the meat was undercooked.  The chef claimed that the dishes were prepared to perfection in the oven, but offered to replace the dish.  Approximately twelve minutes later, a slightly more cooked serving of chicken was presented to me.  I decided to salvage what I could and attribute the experience to a single bad day.  The pickled vegetables and the garlic sauce were the standout components of the entree.  Specifically, the garlic sauce was truly exceptional!  

A short time after that, I brought my mother to dine with me.  We ordered the lamb kabob entree to share.  Unfortunately, she was unimpressed with the kabobs, as her mind was preoccupied with Byblos' lamb shanks, which she holds in high regard (Byblos' lamb is indeed exceptional).  It became apparent that the hummus at this establishment leaves a lot to be desired.  However, I still found the garlic sauce to be outstanding!  It pairs exceptionally well with the tabouli/tabouleh (both are correct spellings).

Fast-forwarding to a period of many months later, I decided to order take-out for my mother and myself: a chicken shawarma sandwich without pickles, accompanied by tomatoes, lettuce, and garlic sauce in a pita; a gyro without pickles and cucumber sauce, consisting of lamb meat and lettuce in a pita; and a gyro with all the fixings for my mother.  Why did it take me such a long time to finally order these sandwiches to-go?  Both types are must-try items: the shawarma is a popular choice among patrons, and one bite is all it takes to understand why.  The combination of the sauce and garlic spread is truly heavenly!  One might assume that a pita with only lamb meat and lettuce sounds too simple to be so delectable, but it is indeed!  The meat is remarkably moist and tender, rendering any condiment unnecessary.  I assure you.  In fact, I recommend ordering one plain and one with the works, and then judging them for yourself; most of the sandwiches cost less than four dollars each!  

Incidentally, patrons may opt for whole wheat pita instead of the standard variety.  Additionally, Haji-Baba pitas, baked at the Haji-Baba bakery located on Apache Boulevard east of the eatery, are available for purchase and may be found on the counter at the register.  

Diners may pay for their take-out in advance and wait for it to be prepared, or they may browse the grocery aisles while waiting and pay for everything at the end.  I suggest that chocolate enthusiasts check out the Swiss chocolate bars available here!  I have tried a few different brands, and I am particularly fond of the Milka brand: milk chocolate with whole hazelnuts, milk, and creamy white layers, as well as plain milk chocolate.  I have a preference for dark chocolate, but was unable to find an allergen-free option.  The flavors are rich and creamy, and the quality of the ingredients is evident.  There are cheaper brands available, but a cursory glance (you may or may not find English among the five or so languages listed on the packaging) will reveal that they contain vegetable fat rather than cocoa butter.  Opt for the higher-end chocolate brands; at two dollars or less per bar, you can acquire a stash without breaking the bank.  

You will likely find something in the grocery section that you wish to purchase, so be sure to remember to collect your take-out order.  The likelihood of you forgetting about food, however, is slim, given that the aromas wafting through the air are mouth-watering!

Several months ago, I had the pleasure of dining at a notable eatery in Phoenix, which offered a unique twist on traditional sushi by providing brown rice as an alternative option - I may be mistaken about this, as my recollection is somewhat hazy due to the passage of time.

One aspect that caught my attention was the complimentary starter that consisted of crispy tempura bits topped with a delectable squid salad - I wish I had ordered another serving of this delightful dish!  In my initial visit, I opted for the Ao Yasai (a medley of fresh gourmet greens infused with ginger) and a sushi roll served with brown rice, which, unfortunately, was a bit pricey considering the modest portion size.  Regrettably, the flavors failed to impress me, and I'm still unable to recall the type of roll I ordered.  It's a shame, really.  

Despite my initial reservations, I'm inclined to give this establishment another chance, perhaps for a casual lunch or dinner gathering with friends, where we can enjoy a variety of appetizers and wine or sake.

On a particular day in September, I made my first visit to a certain upscale restaurant.  I gave it a mediocre rating of two and a half stars...

As I stepped inside, I was immediately struck by the dim lighting- a pet peeve of mine.  Furthermore, the service seemed either frazzled or standoffish.  It was four o'clock and fifteen minutes past the hour, which meant the doors had just opened fifteen minutes prior, and there were not many patrons waiting to be seated.  (There were approximately eight individuals at the bar area.)  I soon encountered my server, whose chilly demeanor and unsmiling face already led me to wonder if this establishment was not the best choice.

After perusing the menu, I decided to order the Prime Burger for a modest price of six dollars.  I also inquired if I could sample a couple of red wines before selecting a glass to order.  I have visited numerous venues where this is not an issue, and occasionally, when I am indecisive, I have even been offered samples willingly!  This particular location was not one of these venues.  My query elicited a more negative reaction from my server, but I did manage to sample two small portions before making my selection.

While I waited for the burger to arrive, I began to power up my laptop- thank goodness I had brought it, as the burger took an inordinate amount of time...  The bar area was quickly filling up, and the servers appeared even more agitated, causing me to wonder what was the source of the commotion.  Finally, just under twenty minutes later, my exquisite burger arrived.  A substantial patty, smothered with cheese and topped with thick-cut, peppered, and smoked bacon, tomato, onion, lettuce, and a pretzel bun, made for a visually appealing dish.  The single large onion ring was a pleasant touch.  The burger was juicy (cooked to my specified medium), quite substantial, and delicious with the cheddar, vegetables, and bun.  The thick-cut bacon, however, was so salty that I had to remove the slices.  I was somewhat disappointed, as it was such a generous portion of bacon.

I would not mind having another Prime burger, minus the bacon, for happy hour again, but I would prefer to dine at a different location. 

Incidentally, as I was savoring my burger, I finally deduced the reason for the harried faces and the servers' hectic demeanor-- it seemed that every patron in the bar area had chosen the burger!  The table of six in front of me all had burgers... At six dollars, it is a bargain for diners, but perhaps not expensive enough to elicit a generous tip?  Hmm... well, not if the servers' attitudes continue to be cold and distant!
Spent 6 hours waiting for a prominent musician's book signing event. Poor event management was unimpressive. It would have been helpful to be informed about the lengthy wait.

I'm not fond of this location.  Parking in a garage to pay for a spot is a hassle.  Paying to shop and dine already, why add parking fees?  It's illogical and unappealing.  Desert Ridge, Tempe Marketplace, or similar destinations are more attractive.

This eatery serves authentic Mexican cuisine. Upon entering, one feels transported to Mexico.  The establishment's appearance may not be impressive, but many Mexican eateries share this trait. The staff's authenticity is evident, as the person taking orders had to summon a colleague fluent in English. The dishes are 100% genuine. I've only tried street tacos so far, which are possibly the best I've had in the US. They come in a double tortilla, likely coated in some type of oil, then pan-fried. Not the healthiest option, but they're extremely tender and flavorful, with the onions and cilantro complementing the carne asada. Their hot sauce enhances the flavors. The tacos are larger than standard street tacos. Four filled me up completely. For $7 (including a can of diet coke), they were a bargain. The staff were friendly and grateful. I'll return. If you've enjoyed Mexican tacos abroad, give this place a try.

I tried a new sub joint in a shopping center despite initial reservations. They offered a Philly cheese steak and fries combo for $5.49. A staff member asked if I'd like to add a drink for $1 extra, and I agreed. My total came out to nearly eight dollars. I thought the tax was unusually high. The drink was actually $1.69, not a significant amount, but I was puzzled by the discrepancy. The sub I received was disappointingly small, roughly the size of a standard Subway six-inch sandwich. I finished it in four bites. Those pre-packaged Philly cheese steak sandwiches from a well-known warehouse store are superior. They're found in the frozen food section, heated in the microwave. I won't be returning to this sub shop. The value was poor. I wouldn't mind paying $8 for mall food if it was genuinely good, but this place wasn't worth even $5.

Some claim In-N-Out Burger is overhyped.  It's not the top burger choice or anything similar.  It still serves a decent burger.  Service here is consistently great.  Orders can take a while, raising questions about the 'fast food' label, yet they ultimately get it correct.  The menu is limited to burgers and fries.  Vegetarian options are scarce.  In-N-Out's food surpasses McDonald's but falls short of Smashburger's appeal.
I visited the location in the evening and missed out on the views, but the meal was satisfying as I wasn't footing the bill.

We caught the end of a live performance here and got a typical LMFMAO song instead. The venue appears to be a pleasant spot with a city view. It must be lovely in the evenings when the sun sets. Service was good despite it being a busy Saturday night. I didn't try the food, so I can't comment on it. There are two rooms, one with the stage and another separate room. Both rooms have many tables.

These burgers wrapped in paper evoke memories of a certain Seattle eatery.  They offer ketchup dipping containers, a welcome change from packets.  This makes drive-thru service more convenient.  The green chile burger I had was cheesy and tasty, with a generous helping of melted cheese and just the right amount of sauce.  Drive-thru wait times can be lengthy, but the payoff is worth it.  The fries are unremarkable but passable.
A meal that's satisfactory, though it comes at a higher cost than expected. Opt for it if your budget allows or dine during the less expensive happy hour period.

They offer multiple options for fries here.  I opt for the standard variety.  My go-to burger is the Smash burger, featuring a Southwestern twist.  It comes with peppers, avocado, and cheese.  A chicken alternative is also available.  Prices are a bit higher than at other quick-service burger joints, but the taste is arguably superior.

A select few have conquered the notorious culinary challenge known as the Hobo Eggs. A paltry nine individuals have successfully completed it over the past six years. I fell woefully short of joining their ranks. The dish's name may be misleading, given its overwhelming potato content.

A popular entertainment venue offers an enjoyable experience despite its less-than-ideal surroundings. Its large size and variety of obstacles make it a great spot to play, with a premium experience like the extended "Ironman" game available at a relatively low cost.

I've never visited the Middle Kingdom but this locale is the closest I've come.  The structures here display Eastern motifs and a sizable body of water teems with aquatic life.  It's an enjoyable destination for photography and strolling.
Their chicken salad was unremarkable.  It wasn't terrible, but not worth going out of your way for.  Maybe next time I'll try the ham.
A tropical twist on a classic beverage is quite impressive. Some casual fare is passable but unremarkable. A beach-inspired ambiance makes dining here enjoyable. The service is satisfactory as well.

We had a pleasant experience at this eatery.  Service was very good, from the hostess to the server.  Food arrived promptly which was beneficial since we had a performance to attend afterwards.  The sushi wasn't the finest I've had but it was passable.  As expected, prices were steep due to its location.  The interior design was appealing, particularly the aquariums along the entrance.  It's a compact venue, yet intimate.  Overall, a satisfactory dining experience if you're in the area and require a speedy sushi option.

A somewhat secluded venue was visited on a Monday evening to meet acquaintances.  Karaoke was available, and surprisingly, there were young children present, one of whom displayed impressive vocal skills.  Service was satisfactory, and the structure seemed relatively modern.  The interior was warmly inviting, yet the expansive outdoor patio offered ample space with bar access.  A Brooklyn-style pizza was ordered, characterized by its thin crust, greasy texture and rich cheesy flavor, proving to be highly satisfying.

A recent visit to a local eatery was marred by subpar service.  Orders took an inordinate amount of time to arrive, and basic tableware was noticeably absent.  Frequent trips to the bar were necessary to procure refreshments, with some visits resulting in extended delays.  On one occasion, the bar was unstaffed.  Under the circumstances, self-service might have been a viable option.  The outdoor seating area is well-suited for enjoying balmy evenings.  The decision to confine live music indoors seems puzzling, given potential noise concerns.  Those who object to the noise might consider alternative accommodations.

I'm reviewing a popular grocery chain without a specific reason. It has a wide selection, which is convenient for shoppers like me who often struggle to find specific items, such as Vanilla Coke Zero. The store's customer service, parking, and cleanliness impressed me, and its modern building is well-maintained. This may become my go-to grocery store.

This eatery stands out for its extended hours, serving food until midnight when many others close early. The menu is extensive, encompassing everything from pasta to burgers. All items I've tried have been satisfactory. The building is modern, boasting a clean, comfortable atmosphere with a large wall-mounted display and plush seating. High ceilings and ample space create a welcoming ambiance. Service is satisfactory, meeting expectations without exceeding them.

A peculiar pairing, yet a novice's verdict is that it's a winner. The accompanying drink is refreshing as well. It comes in a glass jar. The chicken has exceptional seasoning that rivals the best. The flavor profile is reminiscent of a certain well-known seasoning blend. This chicken surpasses the likes of a popular fried chicken chain. The combination of sweet and savory is a nice contrast. You'll likely enjoy it.

It's an average spot, overhyped in my view.  Thin crust pizza, not greasy like some other places, more upscale.  Service was fine, dim lighting, pricey.  Nothing stands out, but I'd return if someone else wanted to go.
Incompetent staff often struggle with even the most basic tasks, such as washing vehicles.
It's underwhelming.  Soft tacos were oversized, an unusual occurrence.  Typically they're smaller and more abundant.
The area appears somewhat unclean. I doubt I'll revisit unless circumstances become dire.

The coffee was quite satisfying.  Food was merely passable.  I've sampled the turkey and early bird sandwiches.  The early bird was decent, but not worth the cost, given its simplicity: a standard bread base with no extras.  I imagine it's more lively in the evenings when it's a wine establishment.

This hike is a must-do, particularly for first-timers.  There are two routes, one significantly more challenging.  Be prepared for a workout, it's a strenuous hike.  Panoramic views and stunning red rock formations await.  Downsides include terrible parking and narrow trails that get congested in some areas.

A popular sports venue boasts impressive architecture.  Parking can be a challenge, though this is a common issue at many similar facilities.  Typically, one must search for a parking spot on the street or further away, then walk to the entrance.  The retractable roof is a notable feature, especially given the local climate.  Our recent visit offered excellent seating and an underground lounge that felt exclusive and trendy.  Another distinctive aspect is the on-site pool, reportedly available for rent at around $3000.  This translates to a relatively affordable $100 per person for groups of thirty.  The main drawback of this stadium is the home team, which has struggled in recent years.

This attraction earns 5 stars mainly for its unique ambiance.  A stroll through the town is enjoyable, evoking an old west atmosphere.  While I didn't explore every nook, the overall experience is quite immersive.  It's a rare find, especially in urban areas like northern cities.  Visitors from afar will appreciate its charm.  A short visit is sufficient to take in the scenery.  The adjacent mountain views are also noteworthy.  A live show and potential mine tour add to its appeal.

I dashed in to fetch a bag of rice for a drenched phone belonging to a friend.  The wait was about 20 minutes as I was held up by two customers who used cheques and one grumbled about the cost of tomatoes.  One wonders.  I won't be back unless I have no other choice.
You can craft your own burger with virtually no bounds.  Various cheeses and condiments plus plant-based and meat options are available.

A low-key eatery with decent grub.  It's quite dim in here, no natural light, which suits me.  I'll have to come back to give karaoke a shot.  The staff were very attentive.  The venue is compact but intimate.
It's a well-known fast food chain. For those on a tight budget, consider cooking at home or investing in a countertop fryer for a DIY solution.

It's a great spot, though I wouldn't recommend it for out-of-towners.  Locals, however, will feel at home here, as it bears little resemblance to Phoenix.  This establishment is nestled in a historic residential area where old homes have been repurposed into trendy bars and cafes.  I appreciate the live music and no cover charge.  The crowd is certainly eclectic.  Having grown up in Seattle, this place reminds me of a popular bar back home - the architecture, the hipster vibe, the music, and the impressive beer selection, which even offered Coors Light, requiring a trip to the back to retrieve it.

A well-known fast-food chain is located here. Service is satisfactory. The overall experience is comparable to other similar establishments. The unique aspect of this location is that it's situated adjacent to a gas station. Occasionally, the drive-thru queue can be quite lengthy.

I'm a fan of this venue.  Some people claim it's geared towards an older demographic, yet I've noticed a diverse crowd.  Alternatively, it's possible my tastes have matured, causing me to prefer establishments with a more subdued atmosphere, free from rowdy patrons often seen in loud bars.  I regularly visit on Wednesdays for an 80s cover band that's quite impressive.  I appreciate the ambiance created by the lighting and the fact that the music quiets down when ordering a drink, allowing for a clear conversation with the bartender.  However, it's pricey, so I usually stick to beer.
Establishments earn additional points due to their miniature employees on site.

The happy hour deals are quite appealing, along with the attentive staff. The establishment's modern architecture and outdoor seating area with misting system make for a pleasant ambiance. Most appetizers are satisfactory. I sampled the Martzan beer but found it unimpressive, so I'll likely opt for lighter brews.

This eatery boasts an impressive menu, alongside nostalgic trinkets adorning the walls and generally satisfactory service. Unfortunately, their rates are exorbitant. A standard lunch combo consisting of a burger, fries, and a soft drink, including tax and gratuity, costs a staggering sum.

I concur with the previous reviewer; employees at this establishment seem eccentric. My latest encounter was disappointing, as the counter staff member was brusque. For years, Subway offered a menu list detailing various bread options, including whole wheat. However, upon my recent visit, this list was inexplicably absent. Not having been to Subway in a while, I inquired about their bread offerings. The staff member gruffly responded before turning away. I settled for white bread. They earn one star for serving edible food and another for its $5 price tag, totaling two stars. Service merits zero stars.

The establishment's amenities are unremarkable. It's housed in an older building with cramped quarters and limited entertainment options. However, the cuisine was exceptional. A signature dish, carne adovada, lived up to its reputation. Essentially, it's slow-cooked pork marinated in a blend of spices topped with melted cheese, served alongside rice and beans smothered in cheese. The flavors pack a punch. I considered trying the habanero burger but ultimately opted out. Perhaps next time. Service was satisfactory, albeit slow, so it's unclear if that's the norm during peak hours. The outdoor seating area is expansive, but we visited during off-peak hours. The atmosphere has a certain charm, a blend of casual and playful. Worth visiting if you enjoy spicy food.

A three-star establishment is satisfactory. The primary advantage of this eatery is its affordability. A meal consisting of three tacos, substantial in terms of meat, rice, beans, and a beverage, costs approximately five dollars and ninety-nine cents. It was excessive, even for someone who rarely leaves food uneaten. The quality of the cuisine is commensurate with the price. The grilled beef was somewhat unremarkable in flavor and lacked the tenderness I prefer. If you require a low-cost option and time is of the essence, this restaurant is passable in an emergency.

Fettucini alfredo was a highlight, but the garlic bread was somewhat underwhelming, being overly crunchy. This eatery is minuscule and situated in an unusual area. The bar area has an inviting atmosphere, so we opted to dine there since table space was limited. Due to its compact size, it gets quite crowded. Reservations may be necessary, as waits can be expected. The bartender was stretched thin, juggling multiple tasks. Wine is served by the glass or carafe only, which is an unusual policy. Despite this, the food was exceptional.
A modest establishment, yet passable for a taco and a beer. A charming barkeep is present, though her name escapes me.
Independent films are a main draw at this theatre, offering a unique viewing experience not available elsewhere. The venue itself has a somewhat vintage, eclectic atmosphere.

This eatery serves excellent morning meals, arguably the finest in the region.  Reasonably priced, it offers a variety of healthy options, excellent service, and a menu featuring local flavors that have become a staple.  Having visited multiple locations, I can attest that they are all satisfactory.  Concerned about its current location, I hope it remains operational.
Staff is often prompt and very knowledgeable, offering courteous assistance.
This year is shaping up to be a standout.  A moderate wait at the door is a plus.  Top-notch service and the cuisine is also praiseworthy.

This area offers a glimpse of Phoenix's less affluent side, a stark contrast to upscale Scottsdale. The scenery is marred by poverty and unattractiveness, a far cry from the wealth and beauty found elsewhere. Rides are subpar, overpriced attractions abound, and deep-fried fare is both mouthwatering and detrimental to one's health.

I'm not convinced this taco joint is the best in town. It's just average, I think. The hype doesn't live up to the food. They're closed on Sundays and Mondays which seems unusual. My first visit was on a Sunday, not knowing they were closed, I waited in my car, then spotted a man yelling at the top of his lungs, which spooked me. I ended up at a different place nearby, Tacos Carbon, and it was actually quite good. That place surpassed this one and the neighborhood wasn't as intimidating. Just be aware, this area isn't the safest. The tacos aren't bad, but they don't stand out from other street tacos in Phoenix.
Food quality is acceptable, though slightly above average.  Service was satisfactory.  Staff are approachable and work well.  The establishment's layout is somewhat limited.

I visited a popular eatery on a Mexican holiday and found it surprisingly quiet.  The grilled meat was delicious.  We were seated in the rear section, which seemed unusual.  A complimentary t-shirt was a nice touch.  The staff provided good service as well.

This store is underwhelming. It's tough to stock every costume item customers demand. Most people leave empty-handed. Advance planning and online shopping might be the way to go. If you're looking to overspend on ordinary items like blue paper products, this is the place.

Going to a popular membership warehouse can be a good option for those who don't mind large serving sizes and crowded conditions. Visiting during less busy periods is advisable; a weekday afternoon seems to be a relatively quiet time.

Some might question the authenticity of their cooking methods, yet the end result is palatable.  Their chicken strips also have a pleasing flavor, despite potential origins.  A fitting slogan could be "Turning lower-grade ingredients into something savory".

They might cook burgers in a microwave.  It still tastes fine.  Who cares if chicken strips come from unwanted chicken parts?  They're still good.  That's a slogan for them: "Burger King: masters of making questionable stuff edible"

A peanut allergy sufferer should avoid this eatery.  There are numerous peanut containers scattered throughout the dining area.  Service on a Monday evening was above average with regular check-ins and timely drink refills.  The food was passable, hot and fresh but lacking in depth of flavor.  The fried onion appetizer was a highlight, though not as impressive as a similar dish at another popular chain.  The steak was satisfactory, though its doneness was uncertain.  It had a chewy texture.  The baked potato was excellent, topped with an array of fixings.  Macaroni and cheese was unremarkable but edible.  This establishment is a run-of-the-mill steakhouse, not exceptional but a reasonable choice for a meal.  Prices are a bit steep, offering little value compared to a rival chain.  However, peanuts are not typically served there, which may be a redeeming factor for some.

This 4-star eatery is a compact, mall-based establishment with a spotless interior.  Friendly service prevails.  Their tacos are a standout.  Prices are slightly higher ($2.50 each) but portions are generous.  It's an excellent choice for upscale, authentic Mexican cuisine.

A popular brewery boasts a scenic view of a notable mountain and Mill Avenue from its expansive outdoor seating area. Their selection of beers is commendable, and the food is satisfactory. Patrons can take advantage of reduced prices during their happy hour, which is a significant perk. Generally, the service is satisfactory. The establishment is quite large and, while slightly upscale, maintains an accessible atmosphere, making it an affordable destination.

Each visit has been met with excellent service. Sales representatives demonstrate a clear understanding of their products and provide the necessary information for a well-informed purchase. They engage in conversation and build rapport with customers. Wait times can be lengthy but are generally manageable. A wider selection of demo phones for the latest models would be appreciated.

After frequent visits, I feel equipped to provide an updated assessment. 

Pros: 
* 24/7 weekend hours
* Reasonable drink prices with a decent selection

Cons: 
* Internet connectivity is woefully inadequate, sluggish doesn't even begin to cover it. Staff seems unbothered, leaving users to struggle with emails on a pace slower than dial-up. 
* Bathrooms are located outside, sometimes requiring a key, forcing users to abandon their belongings. This also means leaving a computer unattended, a less-than-ideal situation.
* Seating is adequate, but not all tables offer power access, limiting productivity.

A downtown store within the Arizona Center is situated. I've shopped here before due to its proximity to my workplace. The store is owned by a local couple who operate two locations, this one and another in Scottsdale's Gainey Ranch. 

It caters mainly to tourists, with prices slightly higher than average. However, the store is well-maintained, staff are friendly and courteous, and a standard selection of items is available.

After discovering this store through online reviews, I visited for the first time today. I was seeking a 3 quart saucepan as my own was malfunctioning. Unfortunately, they didn't have one, so I purchased a candle instead. 

I appreciated this store for several reasons. The assortment of gently used kitchen equipment was nice, with everything in good condition. They had a little bit of everything, including pots and pans, barware, dishes, cookbooks, and other assorted items. 

Although I left without the saucepan, I'd gladly return. The staff was friendly, the selection was excellent, and prices were reasonable. This store is now on my list of consignment shops. Be aware that parking is tight.

A casual diner here, not an aficionado of Mexican cuisine, occasionally craves it.  Never having dined at this particular eatery, I decided to give it a try this time. 

The positives were the vibrant decor - plenty of bright colors and matching decor.  Service was excellent, I had a pleasant time.

However, I found the food overpriced, and it didn't impress me much.  I ordered two tacos and a bowl of tortilla chicken soup.  The portion was small, and I was disappointed.  It was good but a bit too spicy for my taste.  The tacos were fine, but I've had bigger, tastier ones from a competitor at half the price.

I could see returning for happy hour or bringing out-of-town visitors to admire the decor and sample their food, but not as a regular customer.  The food was just okay, and the price was too high for what I got.

I regularly stop by this busy convenience store in the mornings before work to pick up whatever I need. The constant flow of customers in and out makes it a lively spot, especially during peak hours. Service is surprisingly speedy, allowing me to grab what I need and leave quickly. The staff is friendly and organized, maintaining a clean environment nearly all the time. They offer competitive fuel prices, decent coffee, and affordable baked goods that outshine many local competitors. The ample number of pumps and parking spaces ensures minimal wait times for fueling and leaving.

A mid-tier cinema has been visited multiple times previously. It's comparable to other similar venues. 

This particular location has 24 screens and offers moderate matinee prices, along with a decent movie selection. Parking and dining options are readily available. The cinema is situated within a large shopping center, with various dining choices nearby.

A repeat visit is anticipated due to a generally satisfactory experience.

Last night, I was torn between cooking and ordering out.  I struggled to decide what to eat.  Should I cook at home or pick something up?  Ultimately, I opted for pizza.

I went to Red Brick for convenience.  It was nearby, I'd never tried it before, and I didn't feel like driving to Barro's.  Upon arrival, the decor caught my eye - clean, attractive, and inviting.  I decided to keep things simple and ordered a small pepperoni pizza from the menu.

I expected a thicker crust, but it was thin and didn't quite live up to my expectations.  It was a bit greasy, too.  I was hoping for better.  It was okay, but not what I was expecting.

They served gelato, which was a pleasant surprise.  I tried the mint flavor, which was tasty.  The gelato made up for the pizza's shortcomings.  If I judged solely on the pizza, I'd give it two stars, but the decor, friendly staff, and gelato bumped it up to three.

I visited this eatery with my mother this morning for breakfast. We were both impressed by the experience. It was our first time there, and we found it quite enjoyable. The establishment is compact, with limited parking, but they do offer valet parking. I'm giving it a score between 3 and 4 stars, but rounding up due to its uniqueness. When I dine at places like this, I have high expectations, so I'll offer both criticism and praise.

Upon entering, we found the interior charming and well-decorated. There's ample seating and a variety of items to browse. However, the ordering process was a bit confusing, and we experienced some frustration. We placed our order and waited, but our names weren't called. I eventually went to the counter and discovered our food had been sitting there for a while, and no one informed us. Our meal was left unattended, and anyone could have taken it.

We were parched and asked for water when we ordered, and were told to get it from a complimentary water station. The glasses were small, and there was no ice. The area was cramped, so we made multiple trips for water. Now for the positives: the food was excellent. My mother and I both loved our experience, and the English muffins were delicious. She even bought a pack to take home. I had eggs rancheros, which was tasty and filling. The fresh fruit and homemade jelly on the English muffin were great. My mother had pancakes and enjoyed them. Overall, a tasty eatery that I'd return to.

I've been frequenting this particular supermarket for a few months now, and it's not unimpressive.  Following a summer renovation, it's seen significant improvements.  A remodel late last year greatly enhanced its appearance.

This store, while not the most modern or cutting-edge location I've visited, still offers an acceptable shopping experience.  It boasts a comprehensive selection of products, including a deli, meat counter, pharmacy, and a decent assortment of groceries and other essentials.

I awarded it four stars for two primary reasons: a recent renovation and a spotless environment.

A recent visit to a local store followed a brief coffee break. Upon entering, I was impressed. The layout reminded me of a certain retail model, albeit with a more upscale atmosphere. While product choices were limited, prices were competitive, and the staff were welcoming. I was informed that this store is owned by a well-known corporation. This was intriguing. I wish their other locations matched this store's standards of cleanliness and ambiance. Despite not making as many purchases as I had hoped, I'm likely to return when in the area.

While heading to the airport, I stopped at a local eatery for a quick meal. Living nearby, I'd never tried it, so this seemed like an ideal opportunity. The experience was passable, with a standard interior and no overwhelming impressions. Despite this, I found it enjoyable. We waited in line and ordered a large beef hot dog with chili, a sausage with toppings, and fries. Both of us were pleased, and I intend to return soon.

I regularly visit a specific Subway outlet for several reasons. It's conveniently located near my workplace at the Arizona Center, making it a convenient option when I'm hungry. 

Although I'm not a fan of Subway in general, I find their food unimpressive and have discovered healthier alternatives elsewhere. During peak hours, there's often a queue, likely due to the large number of people taking their lunch break at the same time. The location is generally tidy, and the staff is adequate. The menu is straightforward, and seating is plentiful, both indoors and outdoors.

I've been devouring books lately and wanted to replenish my lunch break reading stash.  After visiting two other used bookstores with no luck, I headed to a well-known retailer. 

I'd been there before but not recently. This chain store has its perks: a well-stocked selection and welcoming staff.  I browsed the aisles, not having a specific title in mind but a general idea of what I was in the mood for. I'm a fan of their discount section and the store's layout, which includes overhead signs and clear signage.

Although I left empty-handed, the experience was enjoyable. The staff was friendly, the hours were convenient, and they offer a service to order out-of-stock titles if needed.

A trip to a local shopping complex turned up a welcome discovery - a Jersey Mike's.  After completing errands and shopping, hunger and fatigue prompted a visit to the eatery.  The place was tidy, with tasteful decor and ample seating.  Outdoor seating was available, but indoor dining was preferred due to the heat.  The #9 sub, featuring turkey, roast beef, cheese, and toppings, was ordered, with a note to hold the bacon.  However, a strip of bacon was added, along with an oversight on the mustard.  After correcting the order, the meal was satisfactory, including chips and a drink.  A complimentary cookie, a white chocolate chunk, was a pleasant surprise, courtesy of the cashier.  Overall, the experience was positive, and Jersey Mike's will be revisited.

I'm a huge fan of Smashburger but my experience at a particular location last night left a sour taste.  After putting it off for a while, I finally visited around 5:30, opting for the all-American burger and onion rings. The place wasn't crowded when I arrived but soon filled up. 

While eating, I needed a drink refill and grabbed a fork for my onion rings, which were smaller than expected. I stood up, took my purse, and headed to the beverage station. As I turned, I saw a bus boy clearing my table, my burger barely touched. I tried to stop him but he didn't notice and took my dinner into the kitchen. I was furious, having paid $10 for a full meal. 

I complained to a burger girl, explaining that I wasn't done eating, and she intervened, telling the bus boy to return my food. He apologized, as did the server. I was still upset and demanded the rest of my meal. They offered to remake it but I was too full. I asked to speak with the manager, but the bus boy disappeared into the kitchen. I left and called the store to speak with the manager, who apologized and offered a gift certificate for a free meal if I return. Despite loving their food, I'm unlikely to visit this location again due to this incident.

A routine purchase awaited, so I visited a local boutique specializing in intimate apparel. Every woman should experience a proper fitting at some point, and this store exceeded expectations. Situated in Scottsdale, near Saba's Western Wear, the shop is a cozy haven with a warm atmosphere, characterized by pink walls and an assortment of bras and accessories for diverse body types.

This boutique caters to women of all shapes, sizes, and backgrounds, offering a comprehensive range of support options, including post-surgical bras. They'll even special order items upon request. Operating hours are limited to Saturdays (10-2 PM) and closed on Sundays; while they advertise by-appointment-only, walk-ins are welcome. I was greeted by a knowledgeable sales associate who answered all my questions. I sought everyday bras, not high-end items, and was pleased to find most prices reasonable ( $40-$70). Fittings are complimentary, and the staff's expertise was refreshing  no pushy sales tactics or misinformation. I discovered they have a Tucson location with a 50-year history and their Scottsdale outpost has been around for 15 years.
