This store delivers genuine service, expert knowledge, and a pressure-free shopping experience.

I had a few unpleasant experiences at a couple of auto parts stores I won't mention. So, I decided to try somewhere new. It's a bit out of my way, but not too far. 

I stopped by for windshield washer fluid for my Jeep before leaving town. I didn't want low-quality stuff, I wanted the good stuff. Everything went smoothly, service was fine, the store was clean and well-stocked, and I got what I needed. I'll consider coming back.

I stumbled upon this place on a whim to see what it had to offer.  A quaint store with a vast assortment of paper and craft supplies.  It's not expansive, yet still manages to cater to all scrapbooking needs.  They even had a workspace on site.  A charming little shop, unfortunately closed on Sundays.

I dropped in at this cinema at the eleventh hour on a friend's behest to catch a film over a long weekend. Never having been to this venue, I was taken aback by its discreet location off a prominent shopping centre's edge. 

Some observations I made during my visit include: 
A) The cinema appears to be aged and compact, likely built in the 1970s and repurposed as an independent filmhouse after a larger, more modern cinema took over the mall.

B) Parking is scarce and challenging; good luck finding a spot, as I did for ten minutes.

C) The cinema itself is passable, but it's transformed into a quaint independent cinema. There are only two ticket counters, and during peak hours, the line can stretch around the corner.

D) On Christmas Day, the patrons were predominantly seniors, with every single person appearing to be over 65. I was the sole non-retiree in the audience. It's not a hub for young, trendy crowds. If you're looking to strike up conversations, this isn't the place; unless you're interested in engaging with a predominantly elderly demographic.

A quaint eatery is quite endearing. Upon arrival, it appears to be a small, casual setup with outdoor seating. Most patrons opt to take their food to go, but seating is available for those who prefer to dine on-site.

Orders are placed at a window, and the food is prepared while customers wait. A small gathering in the parking lot added to the ambiance. I ordered takeout, opting for BBQ Brisket, which was decent. The smoked flavor was a highlight, and the BBQ sauce was served on the side for added customization.

The menu is compact but satisfying, and prices are reasonable. The makeshift dining area caught my attention, with a humorous sign above reading "man cave." The establishment is charming, and I recommend takeout, although parking can be tight. It's a pleasant spot with a few minor drawbacks.

I attended a book club yesterday, but I won't be back anytime soon. The afternoon began well but ended poorly. Upon arrival, the restaurant was almost empty and our server was overly attentive, constantly checking on us to order. I wasn't hungry but felt obligated to order due to her persistence. I chose an American hot dog plate with fries and a Coke. Others eventually ordered but one girl's sliders were overlooked and never received. When she complained to the server, she seemed as surprised as we were. Service declined after food delivery, with the restaurant quickly filling with hockey fans. Our server disappeared, so I asked a manager for our bill. When it arrived, we had to return it for splitting. As a sports bar, it failed to provide adequate service. Our table felt neglected, with no drink refills and needing to flag down servers for the bill. I won't return due to poor food and service.

I'm disappointed to leave a negative review but my experience was underwhelming.  Dining here last night, I wasn't eager to return.  Being hungry and seeking a change, I tried this place after driving by numerous times.  I paid $11.50 for a meal and found it unimpressive.  I customized my dish, but the meat looked off and the serving bowls were small.  Choices were limited to meat, pork, chicken, and fish; I chose meat.  I added some veggies, sauces, and the cook grilled it; it was fine, but the meat was unpalatable due to its shaved texture and toughness.  Veggies and toppings were fresh, though limited, with an overemphasis on salad items like tomatoes, cucumbers, carrots, and celery.  Staff was friendly and helpful, and the establishment appears to have been a former fast food joint.

A newcomer to this part of town, I've been searching for a decent BBQ spot since my go-to places are on the other side.  A few weeks back, I stumbled upon this joint and went back for a repeat visit after a positive first experience. However, it didn't live up to my recollection. 

The first time I stopped by on a Saturday night, it was almost deserted. Tonight, it was a bit busier. I went to the counter to peruse the menu, and the person taking orders answered my questions. I'm certain I mentioned dining in, but she seemed to think I was picking up. I'm not sure how the mix-up occurred, but it should've been a red flag when she suggested I wait at the bar. I declined, opting to sit in the back. 

I ordered the Brisket sandwich and waited in the back. Other patrons who arrived before me received their food, and eventually, my order was ready. When she delivered the other orders, she said, "Your food's ready." I thought she'd bring it out like the others. The food arrived in a to-go box with no drink, so I requested a plate. She apologized and took the food back. I then went to the counter for a drink, only to find the initial staff member engaged with the cook, whispering and glancing my way. As I approached, they stopped talking, looked down, and scattered. Maybe I'm a problematic customer or just being paranoid from fatigue. My food eventually arrived on a plate, and the brisket was passable. If I'd reviewed it initially, I'd have given it 4 or 5 stars, but now, it's a 3.

On a recent evening out, hunger had set in.  We disembarked at Mill and sought a meal.  A brief stroll down the street led us to a local eatery.  The nameplate read "Silvermine Subs".  It was a serendipitous find.

Although a newcomer to this spot, I was pleased with the experience.  The unpretentious setting belied the quality of the food.  A diverse selection of hot and cold subs, accompanied by various side items and combo meals, was available.  I opted for the King Bullion, which hit the spot.  The small sub (5 inches) paired well with a large drink and some crisps.  Service was prompt.  The establishment appears to be a popular haunt among students, likely due to its proximity to the light rail on Mill.

I start my day with a coffee and a snack near my workplace, as it's conveniently located. While I'm not particularly fond of this establishment, it remains a convenient option due to its proximity. Their shortcomings are numerous, yet I continue to visit, as it's a familiar choice. 

The service is often sluggish, the coffee counter is frequently out of stock, and I frequently have to request refills on creamer. At peak hours, like 7 am, long lines are common due to the slow service. Their bagels are unimpressive, but I opt for muffins instead, which are generally satisfactory, and the prices are reasonable. 

Overall, this place isn't terrible, but it has become uninspiring over time, leaving me craving better service, superior baked goods, and a more distinctive atmosphere.

Last night, I visited a local eatery to test it out and found it wasn't half bad. It's a long-standing, family-owned restaurant that appears to have been around for ages. The menu is extensive, offering a range of options. I ordered the classic gyro and a Greek salad, which I enjoyed greatly. The food was generous and flavorful, providing excellent value for the price. I highly recommend trying this place, as the gyros are well worth the cost. It's a no-frills establishment, but the food compensates for the lack of ambiance; note that it's closed on Sundays.

I was really looking forward to this place but my experience was a letdown. I've seen them popping up all over the valley and thought they'd be a decent spot for wings and a drink. Although I still think that, my stomach disagrees. I was underwhelmed with my visit and don't see myself returning anytime soon. 

I was craving something different for dinner the other night, something off the beaten path. I didn't want to break the bank or go all out, just something new. I stopped by a wing joint after craving chicken wings, not from a certain fast food place, so I ended up here. 

The eatery isn't huge but has enough seating. I studied the menu, asked a few questions and ordered the 3-piece chicken wing combo at a reasonable price. I went with BBQ flavor. 

The food arrived within 10 minutes. I couldn't finish it. The fries were extremely salty and tasted odd, I think they were spicy. My tongue was confused. The wings were smothered in BBQ sauce - it was like they just dumped BBQ sauce on top of them. It was too much for me to handle. Even after scraping some off, I couldn't finish the rest. 

My stomach was upset the rest of the night. It didn't agree with what I ate. I woke up in the middle of the night feeling queasy but luckily didn't throw up. It was too much for my stomach to handle. I won't be back anytime soon.

I'd been to this eatery before, but it had been a while.  After the horse show on Saturday, I stopped in with a friend as we were famished, and he wanted a drink. It seemed like a good time to try their food since it had been a while for me.

Their menu offered a range of options, including a full bar. On a Saturday around 5, we were the only patrons besides a family in the corner and a few people at the bar. It was surprisingly quiet.

Service was good, my friend ordered a bloody mary and quesadillas, while I had sliders and sweet potato fries. Prices were reasonable, but the place was nearly empty.

I got my fix and was glad I went, leaving feeling full with a tasty side of sweet potato fries.

Who wouldn't be a fan of this library?  Its a real showstopper, especially given its unique blend of modern style.  I've been here twice, and each time I'm struck by its impressive design.  Constructed from steel and glass, it's a true gem.  Sleek elevators, gleaming pools, and artwork throughout make it a visual treat. 

If all libraries were as engaging as this one, attendance would likely increase.  With five floors, each with its own distinct character, it's a destination worth revisiting.  I'm already looking forward to my next visit.

A popular pizza chain fell short for this diner, who loves pizza.  On a quiet Sunday evening, a couple was warmly greeted and seated in a large booth meant for six, despite smaller booths being available.  They ordered a foccacia appetizer, which impressed, but the server had to remake a mojito due to a lack of mint.  The diner's Santa Fe Chicken Pizza was fine, but service was slow.  A friendly server handled their requests, but seemed overwhelmed, and the diner would still return for another meal.

Looking for a change of pace on a holiday weekend, I searched Yelp and found an intriguing eatery. Located in a business area, it stood out for its non-traditional setting in a warehouse. The decor had a subtle, earthy feel, thanks to leaf motifs, despite the cuisine not being Greek. 

Upon entering, I was promptly seated and ordered breakfast early in the day. The server was knowledgeable and friendly, and the French toast on cinnamon bread was exceptional. I devoured it quickly, savoring its deliciousness. 

This place has a cozy atmosphere, diverging from the typical trendy breakfast spots. The prices were reasonable, making it a great value. I'd consider bringing my mom here, as it seemed family-friendly and attracted an older crowd, likely drawn in by the early morning hours. I'll be back.

This eatery isn't unimpressive.  It compensates for its shortcomings with its strengths, making it an average spot.  The dining experience is casual, with orders placed at the counter and collected upon completion.  The ambiance is vibrant, and the menu offers a decent variety.  Prices are reasonable, but I encountered some issues with my order's billing.

A basic combo meal costs $5.95, including fries and a drink.  This is a plus, especially for those who consume a lot of beverages.  However, upgrading to alternative fries incurs an extra cost, which I found disappointing.  I opted for sweet potato fries as a treat, but they charged me a la carte, doubling the price.  The sweet potato fries cost $2.95, which I deemed excessive.  While the food is enjoyable, it's not worth the extra charge.

Service was friendly and attentive, with the manager ensuring our satisfaction.  The food was satisfying and flavorful.  As an alternative to fast food, it's a suitable option for a quick meal.  Next time, I'll stick with regular fries to avoid the additional charge.  This eatery is worth trying.

I'd often pass by this eatery on the lightrail but never stopped until now since they lack their own stop and require a drive down. Plus, they close at 4 on Saturdays and are shut on Sundays. I finally dragged myself there on a Saturday for some BBQ. The place is in a tidy strip mall with decent parking. It has enough seating and you order at the counter, no waiter service. I'm okay with that.

They offer lunch and dinner options; I chose a Beef Brisket sandwich due to not being too hungry for a full dinner plate. The lunch menu is  la carte, with no sides. The staff suggested the dinner plate, which comes with sides, is a better value but only a few dollars more. I opted for the smaller option.

The sandwich was decent, not the best, but I enjoyed my visit. I'll likely return to try the dinner plate, as this place seems legitimate, clean, and has a full menu. I rated it 3 stars since I wasn't blown away, but it's worth a try.

After being rained out at a popular horse show, I was famished.  I had planned to dine there, but the mud and rain made me leave early.  Driving down Scottsdale Road, I pondered what to eat, seeking something filling, not fast food, that wouldn't break the bank.  Spotting a well-known deli, I pulled over.  I'd previously frequented their location in a nearby suburb, but not this one.  Their menus are uniform across locations; you order, pay, and they bring your food out.  I ordered a half sandwich with a salad, which included a self-serve salad bar.  Unfortunately, they were out of the Cesar dressing I wanted, so I made do.  The food is good, but the ordering process is a bit clunky for me.  Prices are steep, but the quantity of food justifies the cost.  I love a good deli sandwich, and this place hit the spot.  It's not authentic, but it's a decent option when you need a hearty meal.  I'd return without hesitation.

I visited this car dealership on a weekend, as my vehicle required maintenance and I wanted to assess the facility. After booking an appointment, I left my vehicle in the designated area. Upon entering the dealership, I was greeted and had a satisfactory experience overall. However, the lengthy wait of approximately three hours is typical for warranty work at most dealerships, so I attribute this to standard protocol. 

My main issue was being approached about purchasing a new vehicle during the service visit, which I found annoying. I'm there for repairs, not sales pitches. It's understandable that sales personnel have their duties, but not every interaction should be a sales opportunity.

3.5 stars

A somewhat unexpected gem sits at the end of a deserted strip mall.  Food here is actually quite good. 

Last night I stopped by to try something new.  The menu boasts a range of options, including Gyros, burgers, wings and Philly steak sandwiches.  A real find.

I opted for a Gyro, which was surprisingly flavorful.  There's ample seating with TVs and menus to suit most tastes.  Hours are convenient too.  Just be aware of the strip mall's desolate surroundings.

A certain casual eatery has its charm, regardless of the time of day.  A recent visit on a Sunday resulted in a sandwich being ordered.  Service was slower than expected, though it's unclear if this is a consistent issue or a one-time occurrence due to the evening timing.  This led to a lost point for prolonged waiting. 

I'm a fan of this eatery.  Its quality isn't poor, but it falls short of exceptional standards.  As the best Arizona has to offer for traditional Jewish cuisine, it's still a decent option.  I'd happily bring my parents here, given my background and experience with similar dishes.  Having grown up with a diverse palate, I'm confident in my judgment.  This establishment stands out in the Valley for its proximity to authentic Jewish fare, even if it's not the most impressive representation.

It's a pleasure to discover an excellent eatery that I consider a great family restaurant. Their menu boasts a wide selection, and the ambiance is laid-back and cozy. Family dining is a breeze here.

Given its Italian theme, this place delivers authentic Italian cuisine without the generic feel of a chain restaurant. You can find an array of traditional dishes, including calzones, pasta, pizza, and salads. The menu is comprehensive, offering plenty of options. They also have a decent selection of wines.

My experience was limited to a Greek salad, but it was satisfying. The casual atmosphere and well-maintained premises are definite pluses. The staff is friendly and welcoming, creating a lovely ambiance.

After a day out with a buddy, we were famished and decided to grab lunch here. It was my first time and I was pleasantly surprised. 

Upon arrival, there are two Julios; we opted for the smaller one, which has a more casual vibe, with self-serve options like nachos and fountain drinks, plus ordering at the counter. The other one's a sit-down restaurant with servers, but we preferred the laid-back atmosphere of Julio's.

I ordered the Burro enchilada with beef, rice, and refried beans, and the prices were very reasonable - I got a lot of food. My friend had mini chimi's and they were delicious. 

I have leftovers for dinner and felt stuffed after eating here for lunch. The place is small, tastefully decorated, has an outdoor patio, and a diverse menu. We'll be back.

After spending time in this area, I've noticed a stark contrast between local grocery stores. Some are well-maintained, modern, and inviting, while others are outdated, grim, and unpleasant to shop in. I prefer stores that have been renovated and offer a pleasant shopping experience. This store falls into the latter category, despite being a bit out of my way. Its modern features make the extra travel worth it. Additionally, having a nearby Bank of America branch is a convenient bonus. This store offers a wide range of products, including a deli, meat, household essentials, and other items one might need. I plan to make regular visits here.

Walking into this particular grocery store, I had lofty expectations, recalling a similar retail establishment from my hometown in the Midwest.  This chain consistently meets high standards in service, products, and overall quality, consistently impressing me. 

The in-store experience was comparable to others in the chain; no surprises here.  A wide selection of fresh produce, wine, meat, and high-quality items were available.  Top-notch service was also provided.

During my visit, I discovered that the store was hosting a live jazz performance outside, which I enjoyed. 

While prices may be a bit steep, this store is ideal for those seeking specific items.  It wouldn't replace my usual grocery store, but it's definitely worth visiting for premium produce, wine, and meat.

A convenient post office is situated off a prominent street between two major intersections. I frequently visit this location to dispatch large packages, purchase postage, and conduct other postal tasks. 

What I appreciate about this post office is its accommodating Saturday hours and extended counter service until 3PM on Saturdays. Additionally, an automated attendant is available in the lobby for after-hours assistance. They offer rented post office boxes, a drive-through drop box for letters, and a selection of supplies for purchase, and the premises are generally well-maintained. 

My rating is three stars due to the common issue of prolonged wait times, consistent with the standard service offered by this postal service. Although there isn't a long line outside, a group of 4-5 people often waits for an extended period. I have spent at least 20 minutes in line, usually when mailing a larger envelope, which typically takes less than 2 minutes to process. 

An automated scale is available in the lobby, but new government regulations restrict the types of items that can be weighed. Furthermore, they do not carry all envelope sizes, so it may be more efficient to prepare packages at home before bringing them to this location.

This location is situated nearby my residence.  I prefer it for several reasons.  Firstly, it offers extremely affordable fuel.  Additionally, they provide complimentary tire inflation.  The parking area is spacious, allowing for effortless vehicle navigation. 

Inside and out, the premises are well-maintained.  It is well-lit and stocks a diverse range of beverages and snacks.  The staff here is courteous and diligent in their upkeep.

I still have a soft spot for a certain grocery store, even after visiting this one. I initially fell for them at a different location near Ray and Kyrene. This store, however, falls short in some way. It offers the same products, an identical layout, but lacks something. 

I still shop here when I need groceries. They consistently offer good deals, their prepackaged meals are tasty and dependable, and the clearance section has some great bargains. My issue lies with this specific store. 

I'll continue to visit this location since it's near my apartment, but in my heart, my preference remains with the store on Ray and Kyrene.

I've been in the valley for a while now and never visited a particular eatery until today. The reason is unclear, but I stopped by for lunch. 

I was impressed by the layout. A salad buffet offered a variety of fresh options, unlike the stale, overused salad bars I've seen elsewhere. The menu included numerous choices, along with beverages, desserts, and excellent breadsticks.

I ordered a combo with a drink, breadsticks, and salad to-go. The counter staff was friendly and welcoming, making my visit enjoyable. I'll definitely return in the future.

I'm a huge fan of deli food.  A few local delis have caught my eye, but this one stands out.  Prices are standard for the area, but slightly more affordable than some others.  You can customize your meal to your liking.  Their matzo ball soup, massive sandwiches, and toppings are a highlight.  

I've visited with coworkers a few times and opted for a lighter meal to avoid a post-lunch snooze at my desk.  The combo of a kosher hot dog, fries, pickle, and small drink costs around $5.24.  A coworker's go-to order is the tuna on whole wheat, which she also enjoys.

What's unusual is the buffet-style service.  You place your order, then collect your food while staff assemble it behind the counter.  Service is swift, and seating is ample even during peak hours.

I'd recommend this eatery to most people; it has several locations in the valley.

I was out and about on New Year's Day, looking for a place to grab a coffee and kill some time, since many places were closed. The local bookstore was still closed and had a long line, so I drove around to find an alternative. I stopped at a strip mall I'd been to before, which had a small coffee shop nestled between other stores. The shop itself was tiny, but I liked it for several reasons. Prices were extremely low, with a 12-ounce Mocha costing just $3.24. The service was also excellent and friendly, so I'd definitely return. However, I gave it three stars because there were only two tables inside, which was a drawback. The internet connection was also spotty, with the staff saying it would be fixed within a few days. As someone who likes to use coffee shops as a workspace, this was a problem for me, especially since there were no outdoor plugs and the heat would be unbearable in the summer.

I stumbled upon a medical facility by chance last year when I required medical attention and didn't have a local primary care physician. My health insurance provider led me to this location. 

Several factors contribute to my positive experience here. Firstly, they have a team of multiple doctors on staff. Additionally, two nurse practitioners are employed here, demonstrating high qualifications. However, the Saturday morning hours are a major draw. Conveniently, I can now visit the doctors on a Saturday. 

The office is spotless and modern. During my last visit, a nurse practitioner was willing to electronically send my prescription to my preferred pharmacy. I'm impressed. I'm glad I found this medical facility.

A weekend of tidying up yielded some items suitable for donation at a local charity outlet.  A large piece of furniture had to be removed from my living space to make room for other belongings, and donating it seemed like the most sensible decision.

This particular outlet is situated within a shopping centre, making it easily visible from the road.  A designated drop-off area is located at the rear of the complex, allowing donors to remain in their vehicles. 

Upon arrival, I found the drop-off process to be streamlined.  A queue of cars had formed, with several volunteers waiting to assist with unloading.  I waited my turn, and a helpful staff member took care of the task for me.

Subsequently, I browsed the store, noticing regular promotions and a diverse range of items on offer.  These included men's and women's clothing, lighting fixtures, and household goods. 

I awarded 5 stars due to A) the organisation's commitment to supporting those in need, B) the efficiency of the drop-off process, and C) the importance of giving back.

I visited a car wash for the first time today and was quite impressed.  It's on a corner in Chandler, with a crossroads nearby named Kyrene. The operation is very organized, clean, and efficient. Everything is automated. Upon entry, there are two lanes to pay at, each equipped with a computerized screen offering various car wash and service options. I chose the basic $5 car wash, their most basic offering. 

After selecting my options on the screen, I inserted payment and the gate lifted, allowing me to drive up to the wash. I stayed in my car, but a staff member directed me into the wash and hosed off my vehicle. They didn't push in my mirrors, which I didn't like as I had to exit to reposition them. I deducted points for that. They do offer free vacuuming, which is a nice bonus. The vacuum stations are shaded, preventing sun exposure while cleaning. They also provide various extra services, including rain treatments. 

However, if the vacuum bays are occupied, you're out of luck. Additionally, there's limited space for adjusting your mirrors if you need to pull off the side. Please check out their website, which is well-designed and lists multiple locations in the valley.

A visitor stopped by a local eatery during a recent holiday break to try their sandwiches. Their initial impression was positive, with an exterior that appeared to be a repurposed fast-food joint, possibly a former McDonald's, due to its two-story design and large window faade. The menu was perused, and a hot pastrami sub was ordered, which proved to be satisfying. Priced fairly, the sub was a good value. The atmosphere was subdued, with only one other customer present during the visit. Happy hour deals were noted, featuring beer pairings with the subs. While the sandwiches were passable, the establishment could benefit from renovations.

I was somewhat peckish and heading out for NYE when I opted to grab some dinner to quell my hunger. I chose Pei Wei, and had a pleasant experience. It's reportedly a toned-down version of P.F. Chang's, and the food and atmosphere were comparable to those at the latter's establishments.

Service was prompt, the location was spotless, and the meal was flavorful. I ordered sweet and sour chicken, which came in generous portions. I'd anticipated a smaller serving size, but that wasn't the case. 

I enjoyed my visit here and would likely return if I found myself in the area and seeking a dependable eatery.

I'm quite fond of this breakfast spot.  I've dined here sporadically at several locations, noticing varying levels of activity.  This branch is busier than others, but not as chaotic as I've seen elsewhere.

I stopped by for breakfast this morning after realizing I was famished.  Given my usual lack of breakfast supplies at home, a visit was in order. 

Service was prompt and efficient, allowing me to grab a quick bite.  I ordered scrambled eggs, an English muffin and hash browns, which hit the spot.  The food was delicious!

I'll likely return.

I stumbled upon an incredible eatery last night.  I'd never heard of Barros until now, but I'm hooked.  I was famished and spent all evening searching for a quick, tasty meal.  A friend had recommended this place, but I'd never checked it out.  So, I pulled in and gave it a shot.  The atmosphere was pleasant, with plenty of seating and a decent crowd.  Their menu offered a wide range of options, including various pizzas, and even some unique choices.  I opted for a simple pepperoni pizza and was pleased with the quick service.  My wait was minimal, and my food arrived in about 20 minutes.  The pizza was a revelation - a truly exceptional pie.  I was thrilled to discover a place serving good pizza in the area.  They also offer beer and wine, which was a nice bonus.  I'd have liked to try a glass of wine, but their selection was limited to just a few options.  I'll be back for more, especially with their thick crust pizzas and great service.

I've dined here a few times, with mixed results. This eatery serves Greek-inspired fare. You order and pay at the counter, receive a table number, and staff deliver your meal when ready.

My first visit was a hit  a Gyro that hit the spot, with flavors that lingered. The second visit was less satisfying; I ordered a bruschetta that didn't quite live up to expectations. Disappointing factors included excessive, cold tomatoes and overly soft bread. My ideal bruschetta features toasted French bread, warm throughout. This place fell short. Next time, I'll stick with the Gyro.

I revisited a new location of a popular eatery with a group of online reviewers. Having been to the downtown site previously and being underwhelmed, I decided to give it another try. This visit was a marked improvement. 

Upon arrival, patrons were already seated. I was pleased to note that my experience here was far superior to the previous one. The establishment was spotless and offered ample parking, a welcome change from the downtown location. The service was also significantly better, with the same menu and cuisine. 

Be prepared for a wait, as this site is extremely popular and serves delicious food.

I used to shop at Dillards frequently due to their vast inventory at reasonable prices.  The store transformed into a clearance center; I'd occasionally visit.  Their reasons for this change are unclear, but they sell discounted Dillards clothing in abundance. 

Items are organized by size and gender, with extensive clearance sections at 50% and 70% off.  Similar clothing in various sizes, alongside some household items, fill the shelves.  Although the store spans two levels, only one is accessible for shopping, with registers near the entrance.  While selection and prices are strong, finding what you need requires searching through the racks.  The upper level is closed off, and shoppers must enter via the main floor. 

The discounts are excellent, making it worth visiting for affordable clothing.  Be prepared to spend time browsing through the racks in a somewhat disorganized manner.  The store's appearance isn't visually appealing, but it's still worth a visit.  My experience has been hit-or-miss; sometimes I find several items I like, while other times I leave empty-handed.  It's not a bad shopping experience.

Someone who's been here before has been forced to return, this time with 2 rugs that desperately needed a good wash.  Unfortunately, their go-to laundry spot had closed, so they had to make do with the nearest alternative.  Having prior experience, they knew what to expect: a place that operates on a card system, where customers load cash onto a card and use it to run their laundry. 

The one redeeming quality here is the affordable prices.  Everything else is a letdown.  The place appears neglected and overdue for a renovation.  The equipment is outdated, and there's always a few machines out of order.  Upon arrival, a burst pipe was being cleaned up.  The restroom is uninviting, and it seems the trash bags are rarely changed.  Although the trash gets emptied, the bags appear to be the same. 

If possible, choose a different location.  This spot is unsanitary, and often the staff is nowhere to be found.  It's hoped that more effort would be put into making this place more presentable, but it seems that's not a priority.  This place is a major disappointment.

A local coffee shop in the Mesa Riverview shopping area near Bass Pro Shops offers a family-owned atmosphere with a range of beverages and treats. They also provide free Wi-Fi. Operating hours are convenient for customers. The only drawback is the seating arrangement, which mainly consists of tables, with only a few couches available for relaxation. The tables are not ideal for prolonged internet use, making it feel like browsing at home. Overall, this is a great, non-chain coffee shop with local artwork, cleanliness, and good service.

A few visits here have yielded fairly positive results.  This store is conveniently situated near a large shopping center and is easily visible from the road.  Its accessibility is a major advantage over a nearby competitor, which often experiences congestion. 

A recent purchase of a digital camera was made here after several smaller transactions. Staff have generally been approachable, although the frequency of interactions varies greatly. In busy periods, they may be preoccupied, but at other times, their attentiveness can be overwhelming. Despite this, a return visit is anticipated due to past experiences.

I dined here last Friday with some companions and must admit, it wasn't terrible.  It's been ages since I've visited an old country buffet  the out of sight out of mind phenomenon has been at play. 

We ordered dinner and for three people, including drinks, the total was approximately $37.  That was a bit more than I had anticipated, around $30 for all of us, but it wasn't a major issue.  I just wasn't prepared to spend nearly $40.  Still, it wasn't bad.

The buffet offered a wide variety of options.  There were multiple stations with diverse dishes, and a grill area where a chef was preparing food  a nice touch.  I sampled a small portion of steak, and it was enjoyable.  Overall, it wasn't a bad experience.  I may return in the future.

It's acknowledged that this writer isn't a fervent advocate of natural foods, yet the merits of one upscale grocery store are undeniable. Their seafood selection stands out, particularly a certain type of smoked fish. 

A well-stocked prepared foods counter offers a convenient option for purchasing a specific type of potato pancake. The store caters to a broad range of tastes, and health-conscious shoppers aren't the only ones who can shop there. Produce appears fresh, and the store itself is massive, spotless, and well-arranged.

However, the prices are a significant drawback.

I stopped by today, being in the area and seeking something new.  I'd heard about this place, but never tried it. 

The experience wasn't terrible, but I wasn't thrilled.  The place was deserted, just one guy eating in the corner.  It was Christmas Eve, so everyone was elsewhere. 

I went to order, but the staff member was preoccupied, so I waited.  I had questions, but she told me to hold on.  I was hungry, so it felt like an eternity.  I ordered a combo - brisket sandwich, mac and cheese, and a drink. 

The food came quickly, but I left disappointed.  The mac and cheese was too runny and over-peppered, so I discarded the rest.  The brisket was okay, but the BBQ sauce lacked flavor and was applied sparingly. 

At BBQ places, I expect extra sauces, but here I only saw an unlabeled vat near the napkins.  I didn't risk adding it to my food. 

The temperature was freezing - I'm from a cold climate, but even for Arizona, it was chilly.  Most places have the heat on, but not this one.  I regret not wearing a coat. 

Overall, I'm open to trying other locations, hoping for a better experience next time.

I tagged along with a friend to a spice shop after lunch, as he needed to pick up some seasonings for an upcoming cooking project. This visit motivated me to improve my culinary skills. The shop was a surprise to me - a store dedicated entirely to spices. Upon entering, the aroma was unmistakable, a pleasant mix of various spices. The store's layout was tidy and well-organized, with a vast array of spices to explore. Each container not only listed ingredients but also provided ideas for usage. Some unique spices caught my attention, and I found it intriguing to see how they could elevate dishes. Spice prices varied greatly, from a few dollars for small containers to over $40 for larger ones. The reusable jars were a thoughtful touch, allowing customers to refill and reuse them. They also sold empty bottles for those who wanted to bottle their own spices from home gardens or special concoctions. The experience was overwhelmingly positive, with friendly staff, fair prices, and an impressive selection.

I've visited this eatery several times.  Its location is somewhat inconvenient, making it a hassle to get to.  It's situated right before the I-10, so if you miss the entrance, you'll have to loop around to turn back. 

I stopped by to grab dinner since I was too apathetic to cook.  They serve massive portions, and one sandwich can easily feed two people.  I recall splitting a sandwich with my mom at a different location many years ago.

Their menu offers a decent variety.  It's broad enough to satisfy most tastes, though from my experience, their offerings aren't particularly exceptional. 

The layout of most of these eateries is consistent.  They have a spacious seating area with booths and tables, as well as a take-out section and a dine-in area. 

I studied the menu and placed my order.  The person behind the counter did an adequate job, but the order pickup was confusing.  While I was on the phone, I moved to a table and discovered my food was ready. 

It was unclear since they'd normally bring the food to the table.  I had to get up and collect it myself.  I was on the phone, and the staff member saw this.  He called me over, and I had to carry a heavy tray while on my phone.  Normally, they'd bring the food out. 

I ended up eating in.  I had half the sandwich wrapped, and ate half at the restaurant with a tasty Caesar salad. 

This place is suitable for kids, families, friends, and dates.  A note: the portions are enormous.

A friend and I stopped by this eatery last night after he mentioned it.  It's a relatively new restaurant, but I'd seen it before so finally tried it out.  
Their menu is quite extensive, covering a range of options including vegetarian, meat, fish and chicken dishes.  They source ingredients locally and mostly serve organic produce.  The interior is tastefully decorated and you seat yourself upon entry.  
My friend did most of the ordering, I opted for the falafel which I enjoyed.  He ordered vegan spinach dip, hummus and a veggie pizza.  Everything arrived in good time, though the veggie pizza had an overabundance of broccoli which I wasn't fond of.  We shared the pizza and I removed the broccoli bits.  
The service was somewhat slow, possibly due to the restaurant being new.  Nonetheless, I'd return and try some of their meat dishes next time.

I've been meaning to try this place out for a while now and since I was in the area, I decided to stop by for lunch. I opted for lunch over dinner, figuring it would be less crowded, and it was, but still bustling with activity. The lunch hour traffic was impressive for a Saturday.

I asked the staff how the ordering process worked and they explained I'd order at the counter while they prepared my food. They also had a wide selection of cold beers and side items. I took my time ordering, feeling no pressure to hurry, and asked plenty of questions about the menu. They offered three types of brisket, each with a different fat content, and I chose the moist brisket with creamed corn and a medium drink. The total came out to $9. 

I grabbed my food and sat down at a picnic table, where I was seated with strangers, but that was fine with me. They provided BBQ sauce, hot sauce, and other condiments at each end of the tables. The brisket was amazing, tender, and flavorful. I loved the taste and portion size.

They also had a convenient hand-washing station after meals, which I appreciated, especially since BBQ can be messy. The station had multiple nozzles, warm water, soap, and towels. 

I deducted a star for one reason: the BBQ sauce was hard to access. While I didn't mind the limited selection, the nozzle on the container made it difficult to dispense the sauce. It required some effort to get it out, which was frustrating. I ended up giving up on using the sauce altogether.

Despite this minor issue, I highly recommend this place. It's worth the visit and they even have a store where you can buy BBQ sauce and other items for home.

The long-awaited light rail service kicked off in December 2008.  I had been counting down the days for its launch.  After moving to this area, I fell for the Rapid shuttle bus system - it was fantastic.  Commuting via bus saved me time and money compared to driving.  The light rail offers a similar advantage, making it a more convenient option for me than driving. 

However, I often ponder what others expect from the light rail.  To help people set realistic expectations, I've compiled a list of its benefits and drawbacks.

Advantages:
A) The light rail is an affordable option, with a daily fare of $2.50 or a monthly pass for $45.  Compare this to your car's fuel consumption - it's likely lower.

B) The trains are spotless and well-maintained, with comfortable air conditioning.

C) The light rail won't outpace your car in terms of speed.  Some reviewers have noted that driving is faster, which is obvious - your car will always be quicker.  The train makes frequent stops and doesn't match your car's speed.  Plan your schedule accordingly, allowing extra time for waiting, travel, and walking to your destination.

D) If you encounter any issues on the train, dial 911 or contact Valley Metro - seriously.

Disadvantages: 

Currently, I ride the light rail to work twice a day, Monday to Friday.  It saves me money on gas and parking fees downtown.  I encourage you to give the light rail a try.

Following a recent visit to a particular eatery, which I had been introduced to at an exclusive gathering of influential reviewers, I found myself compelled to return and experience it firsthand.

We ordered the porco pizza, which featured pulled pork, serrano chilies, and other delectable ingredients. The thin, roasted crust at this eatery is a particular favourite of mine.

It's worth noting that the eatery struggled to keep up with the food demand at the event, to the point where I found myself waiting, along with others, by the kitchen door, in the hopes of securing some food before it was depleted.

A certain fast-food establishment, often associated with the Big Apple, has proven to be a satisfactory alternative to the typical quick-service options. In comparison to other popular chains, such as Subway and Quiznos, this eatery stands out for its welcoming atmosphere and genuine staff.  If this particular establishment were situated closer to my workplace, I would likely become a more frequent customer.

A family member and I made an unplanned stop at this eatery after catching sight of it while cruising by in search of a non-traditional, non-franchise dinner option that was:

1. Not a quick-service establishment,
2. Not a part of a large, national chain.

I consider this discovery to be a fortunate find.  Our server, whose name was not particularly memorable, provided very satisfactory service.

He addressed several questions that the family member had and helped alleviate her initial apprehensions about the cuisine.

We began our meal by sharing an order of papas rellenas, essentially large balls of mashed potato that are filled with a Creole-style ground beef mixture, coated in a light batter, and then deep-fried.  This dish was essentially a fried meat and potato combination, which was quite palatable.

Next, we shared a sandwich, the pan con lechon, which consisted of pulled pork, sauted onions, and mayonnaise served on fresh bread.  This dish was also quite palatable and large enough to be shared between two people.

We concluded our meal by sharing an order of dulce de leche.  Although this dessert was not particularly large, the two of us were barely able to finish it, as it was extremely rich.  The dessert featured great caramel flavors combined with wholesome vanilla and cinnamon, and perhaps a hint of rosewater or another subtle ingredient.

The prices at this establishment were reasonable.  Our appetizer, sandwich, and dessert combined to cost approximately $20.

A popular eatery in the downtown area is worth a visit, despite not entirely meeting the expectations of those familiar with a certain regional cuisine.  While the corned beef, though satisfying, deviates from the traditional style commonly found in certain metropolitan areas on the eastern seaboard, it is still a commendable offering.  This variation, often referred to as "goyeshe" corned beef, is indeed a distinct culinary experience.

I opted for a sandwich that drew inspiration from a classic deli staple, consisting of a toasted onion roll topped with grilled sauerkraut, melted Swiss cheese, and a generous portion of corned beef.  The combination was a delightful twist on a familiar favourite.

The atmosphere within the establishment has a somewhat institutional feel, reminiscent of a large cafeteria, yet this characteristic does not detract from the dining experience.  The food is prepared quickly and consistently meets a high standard of quality.  In the future, I would not hesitate to return for a meal if I found myself in the vicinity, drawn by the abundance of seating and the serene outdoor patio area, complete with a tranquil Koi pond.

A certain popular coffee chain, @DunkinDonuts, had long been a mere afterthought to me, and I could have easily done without it until I spent several years residing in the Boston area, where my life became inextricably intertwined with its offerings.  Then, I became hopelessly enamored with the energizing elixir you so conveniently dispense in a cup.

For goodness' sake, your outlets seemed to be omnipresent along route 1, incessantly beckoning passersby with the siren song of your invigorating brew.  As a result, I found myself growing accustomed to a daily ritual of visiting you, at least once a day.

Well, I've now been residing in the Phoenix area for three years, and it appears that you have been following me, albeit in a most welcome manner.  It's actually quite pleasing to see your presence in the farthest reaches of the Phoenix area, @DunkinDonutsPHX.

However, let us not forget that, at the end of the day, it's all about the coffee.
